"use strict";(self.webpackChunk_N_E=self.webpackChunk_N_E||[]).push([[7629],{7629:e=>{e.exports=JSON.parse('{"id":2,"title":"Chapter 2: The Content of Consciousness and the World of Ideas","description":"","content":{"html":"<h2 id=\\"a5128dc6-a3bb-4733-ae7e-03bbfa56a0e0\\">Introduction</h2>\\n<p>The purpose of this chapter is to explain how human beings perceive the world, think, create, find solutions, and advance humanity concretely. These questions are fundamental, because to understand the world, we must first understand how we understand it. And this issue is far from straightforward, as evidenced by the existence of optical illusions.</p>\\n<p>For example, in the following image (<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Checker_shadow_illusion\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">Adelson\'s checkerboard</a>), squares A and B are the same color, but our brain\'s unconscious processing produces a conscious perception in which these squares appear to be different colors (don\'t take my word for it—take screenshots to verify this for yourselves).</p>\\n<a href=\\"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:grey_square_optical_illusion.svg\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">\\n<img src=\\"/media/grey_square_optical_illusion.svg\\" style=\\"display:block;width:100%;height:auto;max-height:70dvh;object-fit:contain;margin-block:1rem;margin:auto;max-width: 500px;\\" />\\n</a>\\n<p>I wanted to present a concrete example here to show that the subject of this chapter is by no means abstract. On the contrary, we are going to address the most concrete subject there is: subjective human experience<sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-1\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-1\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">1</a></sup>. In other words, we are going to explore the content of human consciousness and how we perceive the world and form ideas.</p>\\n<p>The goal of this exploration is to highlight a key idea: <em>based on a set of \\"elementary experiences\\" and a language to combine them, human beings can construct an infinite number of ideas. This allows them to see the invisible, the past, and the future, and to develop all kinds of technology, art, culture, and so on.</em></p>\\n<p>To arrive at this idea in this chapter, we will present 10 intermediate insights in detail:</p>\\n<img src=\\"/media/realite_xp_conscience_en.svg\\" style=\\"display:block;width:100%;height:auto;max-height:70dvh;object-fit:contain;margin-block:1rem;margin:auto;max-width: 800px;\\" />\\n<ul>\\n<li><em>Human beings can only access reality through subjective human experiences.</em></li>\\n<li><em>Human beings can only perceive what their senses allow them to perceive.</em></li>\\n<li><em>Everything that is not directly perceptible to the senses must be translated into a form that can be interpreted by the senses in order to be accessible and usable by human beings.</em></li>\\n<li><em>Language allows us to precisely encode what is not directly perceptible by the senses into a form understandable to humans. In other words, language allows us to access abstract realities that transcend our \\"elementary experiences\\".</em></li>\\n<li><em>All words in human languages symbolize a human experience or a combination of elementary human experiences stemming from the innate senses of the human brain. These elementary human experiences are the elementary particles of language, the atoms of language.</em></li>\\n<li><em>Our elementary senses allow us to perceive multiple dimensions of reality.</em></li>\\n<li><em>Synesthesia allows us to connect the multiple dimensions we perceive to create a multidimensional image of reality.</em></li>\\n<li><em>The best way to understand an idea is to experience it through an elementary sense. More broadly, the only way to understand something is to connect it to an experience we have had.</em></li>\\n<li><em>If human beings can only grasp the abstract through symbols, then these symbols shape their perceptions. In other words, when we go beyond the limits of elementary senses like sight or geometry, we never see reality itself, but only symbols that are supposed to indicate the presence of that reality. And these symbols can mislead us.</em></li>\\n<li><em>Our representation of the world and the symbols we use to describe it are shaped by the experiences we have had. So much so that our ideas and opinions are an expression of our lived experiences. Very often, \\"thinking\\" simply consists of putting our experiences into words.</em></li>\\n</ul>\\n<p>That being said, let\'s start at the beginning, that is, with consciousness.</p>\\n<h2 id=\\"fadce076-7065-4f6e-8ffd-cfb29db2b3d7\\">Consciousness According to Modern Science</h2>\\n<p>What is consciousness? For most of my life, I sought an answer in philosophy, spirituality, and meditation practices. Then, one day two years ago, I realized I had never asked myself a basic question: what do scientists say on the subject? So I asked ChatGPT for reading recommendations, and it suggested Stanislas Dehaene\'s book <em>Consciousness and the Brain</em>. As I read this book, I discovered that significant progress had already been made and, above all, that science and spirituality were no longer opposed. Spirituality—that is, what is unique to the human mind, and thus the subjective human experience—is no longer denied by scientists<sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-2\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-2\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">2</a></sup>. On the contrary, they have been studying it in detail since the late 1980s.</p>\\n<p>Concretely, 40 years ago, neuroscientists began studying consciousness based on a simple principle: treating subjective experiences as objective data.</p>\\n<p><em>\\"If someone tells me they\'re floating outside their body, that their brain contains a chip implanted by the CIA, or that they\'re conversing with Julius Caesar in their dreams, I don\'t take their accounts at face value. And yet, in a sense, even situations as strange as these must be taken seriously, because if the person isn\'t lying, they correspond to genuine mental states that the psychologist will have to explain. The only appropriate approach is to treat these subjective reports as raw data.\\"</em><br>\\nStanislas Dehaene (neuroscientist), <em>Consciousness and the Brain</em> (2014), section <em>\\"Making the Subjective a Science\\"</em></p>\\n<p>From that point on, scientific research on consciousness has simply exploded. And today, in their laboratories, neuroscientists are able<sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-3\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-3\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">3</a></sup> to:</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li>To induce light hallucinations through transcranial magnetic stimulation, allowing researchers to move a small halo of light within the volunteer\'s conscious field of vision</li>\\n<li>To identify what specific stimuli certain individual neurons respond to (for example, to identify which neuron specifically activates in response to the words \\"Eiffel Tower\\" and to the sight of a photo of the monument in question)</li>\\n<li>To artificially induce temporary \\"out-of-body experiences\\" through combinations of visual and tactile signals</li>\\n</ul>\\n<p>But, above all, significant progress has been made regarding how we perceive the world. In particular, regarding the neurological basis of our subjective experience (such as the perception of quantities, geometry, and the manipulation of language and symbols). For example, blind people \\"see\\" geometric shapes like squares and circles, because the perception of these shapes is part of the basic functions of the human brain that we all share. These functions are encoded in our genes, just as the program for building a nest is written into the genome of birds and the program for building a web into the genome of spiders<sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-4\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-4\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">4</a></sup>. And it is from these basic functions that we create ideas and all kinds of art and technology. That is what we will explore in this chapter. And, to begin with, I must clarify what I mean by \\"subjective experience\\".</p>\\n<h2 id=\\"08060ae3-a0dd-4e8c-a961-7aeff293635d\\">What Is an Experience?</h2>\\n<p>The purpose of this section is to introduce the following question: Is it possible to know or perceive the world in any way other than through experience?</p>\\n<p>Let\'s start by introducing the concept of \\"subjective experience\\" with a short exercise. Take a deep breath and ask yourself what you\'re feeling. Do you feel the air caressing your nostrils and your chest expanding? Perhaps you feel a sense of calm. Take a moment to truly \\"experience\\" your breath by observing what you feel. Explore your \\"inner experience\\"—what is happening inside you. Explore this subjective human experience that is breathing<sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-5\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-5\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">5</a></sup>.</p>\\n<p>From there, we can establish a definition: <em>a human experience refers to what an individual lives through and feels internally at a given moment in a particular situation.</em> This includes sensory perceptions (image, sound, touch, smell, temperature, etc.), emotional perceptions (fear, joy, sadness, justice, etc.), intellectual perceptions (geometry, quantity, etc.), and everything that may not be clearly describable in words (we will detail these perceptions later in this chapter).</p>\\n<p>Of course, there is nothing revolutionary about this definition. In everyday language, we readily speak of \\"having an experience\\" or a \\"professional experience\\". But this second concept raises a problem. For when we speak of a professional experience, we are referring to the overall sum of what an individual has gone through over months or years in a particular job. We are not interested in what they experienced every minute or second of their professional life. Yet no one lives a \\"professional experience\\". The only thing we experience is a succession of very brief experiences.</p>\\n<p>Every minute, we have a multitude of experiences. And what we call \\"professional experience\\" or even \\"the experience of breathing\\" is a highly simplified summary of this multitude of experiences lived over a period of time, long or short. For example, our \\"experience of breathing\\" is actually made up of a multitude of smaller, more concrete experiences, such as feeling the air brush against our nostrils and our chest expand. Thus, behind the apparent obviousness of the concept of \\"breathing\\" lies a multitude of small, very down-to-earth experiences.</p>\\n<p>This raises a question: can we understand the concept of \\"breathing\\" without having had at least one of these small experiences? More broadly: can we know or perceive the world in any way other than through concrete experience?</p>\\n<p>Quite logically, one might conclude that the answer must be \\"no\\" in most cases. If you had never breathed or seen anyone breathe, you wouldn\'t understand what it means to breathe. Or, more simply, if you had never seen an elephant or heard anyone talk about one, you wouldn\'t know what an elephant is.</p>\\n<p>But are there exceptions? For example, in science? Do scientists study things that go beyond their own experience?</p>\\n<p>These questions may seem a bit philosophical or abstract. Yet all of modern science is based on this notion of \\"experience\\". And that is what we will explore in the next section by describing how scientific research works today. This will allow us to answer the questions posed.</p>\\n<h2 id=\\"5cdbb3a7-aed0-4b8f-b158-46618e0e43a1\\">The Structure of Scientific Research</h2>\\n<p><em>Can we know or perceive the world in any way other than through subjective experience? And do scientists study things that go beyond their own subjective experience?</em></p>\\n<p>To answer these questions, I will explain the origin of the initial insight presented in the introduction: <em>human beings can only access reality through human experiences, that is, their \\"inner experience\\".</em></p>\\n<p>My entire line of thought began with a question: how do scientists verify a mathematical theory? How does a mathematician know if his theory is true or false? More simply, how does a mathematician verify that 1+1=2?</p>\\n<p>The answer is disconcerting. Mathematicians do exactly what you and I do. They look at the equation 1+1=2 and verify it in their \\"inner experience\\". And they do exactly the same thing for all their other equations and theories. In other words, they experience these equations, and if they seem right to them, then they must be right.</p>\\n<p>All of science is based on this principle. Naturally, scientists test their theories in the real world as much as possible. But, ultimately, only their \\"inner experience\\" allows them to judge whether a theory or a result is right or wrong, particularly by analyzing the results of their experiments<sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-6\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-6\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">6</a></sup>.</p>\\n<p>As you might expect, this method is not infallible and can lead to human error. Therefore, to limit these errors, scientists ask other scientists to verify their theory through their own \\"inner experience;\\" this is what is known as \\"peer review\\".</p>\\n<img src=\\"/media/organigramme_recherche_en.svg\\" style=\\"display:block;width:100%;height:auto;max-height:70dvh;object-fit:contain;margin-block:1rem;margin:auto;max-width: 600px;\\" />\\n<p>Concretely, when a scientist finishes writing a paper in which they present their theory or the results of their experiments, they submit it to a \\"peer review committee\\". This committee typically consists of 5 to 10 scientists who are experts in the field in question. These experts then evaluate the content and scientific rigor of the paper based on their own \\"inner experiences\\". And if the article seems objectively right to them, it may be published in a scientific journal<sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-7\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-7\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">7</a></sup>.</p>\\n<p>It should be noted that scientific journals play a fundamental role in scientific research by organizing this process (although their monopoly is being challenged by the internet). And, more broadly, by:</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li>Reviewing and validating research (which involves selecting articles for review and recruiting experts)</li>\\n<li>Disseminating scientific knowledge and discoveries</li>\\n<li>Storing and archiving this knowledge</li>\\n</ul>\\n<p>The central idea I want to highlight here is that the entire social organization of science rests on the \\"inner experiences\\" of the human beings who participate in it. Thus, behind its rigid and cold exterior, science is, on the contrary, very human. It is literally a story of men and women who collaborate rigorously in an attempt to unlock the secrets of the universe. In some respects, science could be defined as \\"the public consensus of reasonable people\\"<sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-8\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-8\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">8</a></sup>.</p>\\n<p>With that in mind, we can answer the question: <em>Do scientists study things that go beyond their own experience?</em></p>\\n<p>Answer: No, scientists study the world only through their personal experience.</p>\\n<p>However, one question remains: Is the \\"inner experience\\" of scientists different from that of other human beings? Did \\"geniuses\\" like Newton and Einstein have access to other dimensions of reality? Did they see the world differently from us?</p>\\n<h2 id=\\"4210e491-0a2b-44b6-acd4-e5514a954f2a\\">Thinking Like Newton and Einstein</h2>\\n<p><em>Did \\"geniuses\\" like Newton and Einstein have access to other dimensions of reality?</em></p>\\n<p>To answer this question, we might ask how Newton and Einstein developed their theories of gravity. For if they revolutionized physics by asking questions that anyone could have asked, then they must have lived in the same reality as we do.</p>\\n<p>Personally, when I heard in school that Newton had his \\"eureka\\" moment upon seeing an apple fall from a tree, I didn\'t understand how that was possible. I couldn\'t see an intuitive connection between an apple falling and the moon\'s orbit. As a result, for a long time I imagined that Newton and the great scientists had access to a reality that was beyond my comprehension.</p>\\n<p>Then I learned the truth about the origin of Newton\'s theory<sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-9\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-9\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">9</a></sup>. It all started with a simple question he asked himself <em>\\"What would happen if <a href=\\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lnEdBE7d_h0\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">I fired a cannonball really hard (knowing that the Earth is round)</a>?\\"</em></p>\\n<img src=\\"/media/principia_newton.jpg\\" style=\\"display:block;width:100%;height:auto;max-height:70dvh;object-fit:contain;margin-block:1rem;margin:auto;max-width: 400px;\\" />\\n<p>And I also discovered <a href=\\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=E5LvA8FHBxs\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">the questions that led Einstein</a> to his theory of gravity:</p>\\n<p><em>\\"What would I feel if I were in a motionless rocket in space? Would it be different from being in a free-falling elevator on Earth? And if the rocket accelerated, would I feel the same as standing on Earth? And if a beam of light passed through that rocket or a free-falling elevator, what would happen? Given that the speed of light is constant, as <a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michelson%E2%80%93Morley_experiment\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">other scientists</a> have already demonstrated.\\"</em></p>\\n<p>In other words, they simply asked themselves questions that no one else had asked. But they didn\'t have access to a reality different from yours and mine. Newton and Einstein saw the same world as we do with their own eyes.</p>\\n<p>We can therefore conclude: <em>Scientists, like all human beings, can only access reality through human experiences—that is, their \\"inner experience\\".</em></p>\\n<p>Now, if scientists can only know the world through concrete experience, how did they manage to create nuclear power plants and the internet without ever seeing or touching an atom? More broadly, how does a human being come to know and interact with what they will never actually see, such as an atom, an electromagnetic wave, or a state? In short, how can we see the invisible, the immaterial, the infinitely large and small, manipulate the infinite, and see into the past and the future? To answer these questions, we must start from the basics. And that is what we will do in the next section.</p>\\n<h2 id=\\"94deef7c-68ae-4c34-beaf-269626820638\\">The Prison of the Senses</h2>\\n<p>In this section, I will present two insights:</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li><em>Human beings can only perceive what their senses allow them to perceive.</em></li>\\n<li><em>Everything that is not directly perceptible to the senses must be translated into a form that can be interpreted by the senses in order to be accessible and usable by human beings.</em></li>\\n</ul>\\n<p>It all started with an observation: I can only see what my eyes allow me to see<sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-10\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-10\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">10</a></sup>. The case of colorblind people illustrates this very concretely. If you are a deuteranope, your eyes lack the cones that detect green. Consequently, you have great difficulty distinguishing orange from green. You will therefore not see the number 6 in orange on a green background in the image below, even though it is clearly visible to the majority of the population.</p>\\n<img src=\\"/media/ishihara_11.png\\" style=\\"display:block;width:100%;height:auto;max-height:70dvh;object-fit:contain;margin-block:1rem;margin:auto;max-width: 400px;\\" />\\n<p>This observation led me to another: the only way to know what the surface of Mars looks like is to use a telescope. Without one, Mars is just another bright spot in the starry sky. In the same way, the only way to know what the flu virus looks like is to observe it under a microscope.</p>\\n<img src=\\"/media/mars_brille.svg\\" style=\\"display:block;width:100%;height:auto;max-height:70dvh;object-fit:contain;margin-block:1rem;margin:auto;max-width: 500px;\\" />\\n<p>When applying the same idea to temperature, an additional challenge arises. The human body has temperature sensors that allow us to roughly estimate temperatures between 0 and +45 \xb0C. But beyond that, we can no longer tell the difference. Below 0 \xb0C, it\'s very cold. And above 45 \xb0C, it\'s very hot. Our bodies can\'t tell the difference between 200 and 300 \xb0C; in both cases, it\'s simply very hot.</p>\\n<p>Of course, we can use a thermometer. But unlike a telescope, which zooms in on an image of Mars, a thermometer doesn\'t simply zoom in on a temperature. Instead, it translates that temperature into symbols that humans can understand: numbers, most of the time.</p>\\n<p>This principle can be generalized. For example, our eyes can only see certain frequencies of the electromagnetic spectrum. We are unable to see or hear radio waves or Wi-Fi<sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-11\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-11\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">11</a></sup>. Yet these waves exist, and technology allows us to detect and interpret them. Your smartphone is literally an extrasensory sensor that allows you to pick up and use the cellular network, Wi-Fi, Bluetooth, and so on. Thus, technology literally allows us to grasp the invisible. And, in the case of the telescope and the microscope, to see the infinitely distant or small.</p>\\n<img src=\\"/media/Electromagnetic_spectrum,_NASA_illustration.jpg\\" style=\\"display:block;width:100%;height:auto;max-height:70dvh;object-fit:contain;margin-block:1rem;margin:auto;\\" />\\n<p>In summary:</p>\\n<img src=\\"/media/general_trad_symbole_en.svg\\" style=\\"display:block;width:100%;height:auto;max-height:70dvh;object-fit:contain;margin-block:1rem;margin:auto;max-width: 600px;\\" />\\n<p>This highlights the two initial insights:</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li><em>Human beings can only perceive what their senses allow them to perceive.</em></li>\\n<li><em>And everything that is not directly perceptible to the senses must be translated into a form that can be interpreted by the senses in order to be accessible and usable by human beings.</em></li>\\n</ul>\\n<p>Now, how? How do we translate the invisible into something usable? For example, how do we translate a temperature below 0 \xb0C or above 45 \xb0C into a number?</p>\\n<h2 id=\\"b77436e2-9505-47a5-b700-c2b0c13ff864\\">Seeing the Invisible</h2>\\n<p>In this section, I will present the following idea: <em>language allows us to precisely encode what is not directly perceptible by the senses into a form understandable to humans.</em></p>\\n<p>To illustrate this idea, we will look at how a thermometer works. Because a thermometer precisely encodes temperatures or temperature variations imperceptible to the human senses into numbers. We are so accustomed to using temperature in Celsius that we forget it was constructed by humans through language, just like all our other concepts. And the example of the thermometer will help us shed light on how these concepts are created. That is, how we encode what lies beyond our senses into a language we understand.</p>\\n<p>Let\'s start at the beginning. The basic principle of the thermometer is based on an experiment that can be directly observed by humans (and was known even before antiquity): cold causes matter to contract, and heat causes it to expand<sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-12\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-12\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">12</a></sup>. Therefore, if you place a liquid in a vertical tube, the lower the temperature, the less space the liquid will occupy, and the lower its level will be. And, conversely, when it gets hot. Thus, the change in the liquid\'s height in the tube will represent the change in temperature.</p>\\n<img src=\\"/media/dilatation_thermique_reduit.png\\" style=\\"display:block;width:100%;height:auto;max-height:70dvh;object-fit:contain;margin-block:1rem;margin:auto;max-width: 650px;\\" />\\n<p>Next, we\'ll add a temperature scale. To construct this scale, we need a high point and a low point. You can choose these reference points freely, but ideally, these limits should correspond to easily observable temperatures. As with the Celsius scale, let\'s choose:</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li>0 = temperature at which ice melts</li>\\n<li>100 = temperature at which water boils</li>\\n</ul>\\n<p>All that remains is to calibrate our thermometer. To do this, we fill a glass tube slightly with a liquid that freezes below 0 \xb0C and boils above 100 \xb0C (such as mercury, which freezes at -39 \xb0C and boils at +356 \xb0C). Then, we place our glass tube in a pot of water and leave it outside to freeze in the winter. Once the water has frozen, bring the pot back inside and:</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li>When the ice begins to melt, mark a line at the mercury level on our thermometer and note 0</li>\\n<li>Next, place the pot on the stove, and when the water begins to boil, mark a new line at the mercury level and note 100</li>\\n<li>Finally, divide the distance between the two marks equally into 101 divisions corresponding to temperatures between 0 and 100 (we can extend this scale in both directions to measure temperatures below 0 \xb0C and above 100 \xb0C)</li>\\n</ul>\\n<p>And voil\xe0—our thermometer is calibrated, and we can use it to accurately measure temperatures between -39 \xb0C and +356 \xb0C (the temperatures at which mercury freezes and boils). In other words, using a system of symbols comprising physical observations and numbers, we have precisely encoded what was not directly perceptible to our senses. Namely, temperatures below 0 \xb0C and above 45 \xb0C, as well as temperature variations that are too small or too widely spaced in time to be distinctly compared by our senses and memory.</p>\\n<p>At first glance, the thermometer and the Celsius scale I just described look like a rudimentary handiwork project. Yet it is on this kind of handiwork that all of science and technology is based. To illustrate this, here are some examples of modern professional thermometers and their measurement ranges:</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li>Bimetallic thermometer (-50 to 300 \xb0C): relies on the expansion of metal rather than that of liquids</li>\\n<li>Resistance thermometer (-200 to 850 \xb0C): relies on changes in electrical resistance, because as an object\'s temperature rises, its electrical resistance also increases (for example, rubber has very high electrical resistivity, meaning it barely conducts electricity, unlike copper, which is used in electrical cables)</li>\\n<li>Optical pyrometers (600 to 5000 \xb0C): based on changes in light or infrared radiation, because when an object becomes hot, it emits light (think of iron turning red, then white when heated)</li>\\n</ul>\\n<p>That being said, we can now highlight one of the basic principles of human language: analogy<sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-13\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-13\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">13</a></sup>. Concretely, the construction of the first thermometer and the degree Celsius is based on two analogies:</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li>\\"A rise in temperature is like the expansion of a liquid\\"</li>\\n<li>\\"The expansion of a liquid in a tube is like an increase in a number\\"</li>\\n</ul>\\n<p>The other thermometers presented are based on the same principle of analogy; the only difference is the analogy itself:</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li>Bimetallic thermometer: a rise in temperature is like the expansion of metal</li>\\n<li>Resistance thermometer: a rise in temperature is like an increase in electrical resistance</li>\\n<li>Optical pyrometers: a rise in temperature is like an increase in light or infrared radiation</li>\\n</ul>\\n<p>We can note something else. These analogies led to the creation of three new concepts:</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li>\\"The rise in temperature is like the expansion of a liquid\\" led to the invention of the concept of the \\"thermoscope\\" (the ancestor of the thermometer, which had no scale)</li>\\n<li>\\"The expansion of a liquid in a tube is like an increase in a number\\" led to the invention of the concepts of the \\"thermometer\\" and the \\"degree Celsius\\"</li>\\n</ul>\\n<p>\xc0 partir de l\xe0, on peut se poser une question\xa0: si certains concepts sont construits \xe0 partir d\'autres concepts, comment ont \xe9t\xe9 construits les premiers concepts\xa0? D\'o\xf9 viennent les concepts comme \\"augmentation\\", \\"temp\xe9rature\\", \\"dilatation\\", \\"liquide\\" et m\xeame les nombres\xa0? Y a-t-il des \\"particules \xe9l\xe9mentaires\\" du langage, comme il existe des \\"particules \xe9l\xe9mentaires\\" de la mati\xe8re ? Et quel rapport avec l\'exp\xe9rience humaine dont nous parlions pr\xe9c\xe9demment\xa0?</p>\\n<p>This raises a question: if certain concepts are built upon other concepts, how were the first concepts formed? Where do concepts like \\"increase\\", \\"temperature\\", \\"expansion\\", \\"liquid\\", and even numbers come from? Are there \\"elementary particles\\" of language, just as there are \\"elementary particles\\" of matter? And how does this relate to the human experience we were discussing earlier?</p>\\n<h2 id=\\"1a3c4e56-c16c-4ef0-802c-333f801dbcbe\\">The Atoms of Language</h2>\\n<p><em>\\"Spoken words are the symbols of mental experience and written words are the symbols of spoken words. Just as all men have not the same writing, so all men have not the same speech sounds, but the mental experiences, which these directly symbolize, are the same for all, as also are those things of which our experiences are the images.\\"</em><br>\\nAristotle (ancient Greek philosopher), <em>Organon</em> (c. 335–322 BCE<sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-14\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-14\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">14</a></sup>)</p>\\n<p>In this section, I will present the following idea: <em>all words in human languages symbolize a human experience or a combination of elementary human experiences stemming from the innate senses of the human brain. These elementary human experiences are the elementary particles of language, the atoms of language.</em></p>\\n<p>The starting point for this insight is an observation: when our ancestors sacrificed an animal to the gods to invoke rain, they assumed that the gods in question possessed a human psychology. The idea of<br>\\ngift and counter-gift (reciprocity) is a purely human behavior that the clouds do not share. And, if there is one or more gods, there is no reason to believe they behave like humans.</p>\\n<p>In other words, our ancestors\' worldview was highly anthropocentric, that is, biased by their own human experience<sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-15\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-15\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">15</a></sup>. They projected their own human functioning onto the gods, without realizing that this functioning was not necessarily universal. And this bias appeared in their language, because the word \\"god\\" corresponded to a very \\"human\\" being who instinctively understood reciprocity.</p>\\n<p>From there, I wondered if the words I used were also biased by my human experience: to go up, to go down, to breathe, to eat, to cut, big, small, a book, a color, a smell, a sound, etc. The result surprised me. Indeed, most of our vocabulary seems to systematically refer to a human experience. For example, when I think of the word \\"go up\\", I feel what it\'s like to climb a staircase, or I picture a person climbing steps. When I think of the word \\"book\\", I see an image of a book. And I instinctively distinguish a \\"big\\" object from a \\"small\\" one.</p>\\n<p>Now, does this apply to all words? To answer that, we can recall what we demonstrated earlier: <em>human beings can only access reality through human experiences, that is, their \\"inner experience\\".</em> Consequently, if a word referred to anything other than human experiences, it would make no sense to us, because we would be unable to access what it designates.</p>\\n<p>Then, I asked myself the questions mentioned earlier: <em>if certain concepts like \\"thermometer\\" are constructed from other concepts, how were the first concepts constructed? Are there \\"elementary particles\\" of language, just as there are \\"elementary particles\\" of matter?</em></p>\\n<p>At that moment, I had just realized that my entire vocabulary referred to human experiences. So I told myself that to truly understand language, one had to understand the experiences to which it referred. So I tried to break down the experiences symbolized by my vocabulary. And I realized that even the word \\"breathing\\" wasn\'t as straightforward as one might think. In reality, as we saw in section 2, when we talk about \\"breathing\\", we\'re referring to multiple \\"elementary experiences\\", such as:</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li>The sensation of temperature and touch in the nostrils</li>\\n<li>The sound of inhaling and exhaling</li>\\n<li>The sensation of the lungs expanding and contracting</li>\\n<li>And potentially all the primary sensations associated with this act, such as the intense sensation one feels when catching one\'s breath after holding it</li>\\n</ul>\\n<img src=\\"/media/xp_mot_respiration_en.svg\\" style=\\"display:block;width:100%;height:auto;max-height:70dvh;object-fit:contain;margin-block:1rem;margin:auto;max-width: 600px;\\" />\\n<p>I soon realized that these \\"elementary experiences\\" were simply the experiences arising from my innate senses. This included, as mentioned earlier: <em>sensory perceptions (image, sound, touch, smell, temperature, etc.), emotional perceptions (fear, joy, sadness, justice, etc.), intellectual perceptions (geometry, quantity, etc.), and everything that cannot be clearly described with words.</em></p>\\n<p>In other words: <em>all words in human languages symbolize a human experience or a combination of elementary human experiences arising from the innate senses of the human brain.</em></p>\\n<p>Presented so briefly, this idea may seem a bit simplistic or theoretical. In the next section, we will therefore illustrate it by drawing on concrete examples of \\"elementary experiences\\".</p>\\n<h2 id=\\"8155f869-3ee0-425d-9649-2edba58b54f8\\">The Language of Thought</h2>\\n<p>The goal of this section is to introduce the existence of a set of elementary building blocks of human thought: innate \\"elementary experiences\\".</p>\\n<p>At first glance, this objective may seem a bit abstract, so let\'s look directly at the simplest \\"elementary experiences\\": sight, smell, taste, hearing, touch (including the perception of temperature), and proprioception<sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-16\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-16\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">16</a></sup>. Concretely, sight is an innate \\"elementary experience\\" that allows us to represent the world and to think.</p>\\n<p>The idea that sight is innate and allows us to mentally reflect on the world may seem obvious. However, the boundary between what is innate and what is not is by no means clear. For example, are numbers and geometry innate? Are the following innate:</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li>Understand 1, 2 and 3 distinctly</li>\\n<li>Mastering addition</li>\\n<li>Distinguishing a square from other geometric shapes</li>\\n</ul>\\n<p>Scientists say yes. And this is no trivial matter, because all it takes is the ability to distinguish 1, 2, and 3 clearly and to master addition to be able to count to infinity by inventing all the other numbers. If we add to that an innate sense of geometry, we can very easily invent the concept of \\"\xb2\\", of the \\"cube\\", and the Pythagorean theorem.</p>\\n<img src=\\"/media/carre_maths.svg\\" style=\\"display:block;width:100%;height:auto;max-height:70dvh;object-fit:contain;margin-block:1rem;margin:auto;max-width: 400px;\\" />\\n<img src=\\"/media/cube_maths.svg\\" style=\\"display:block;width:100%;height:auto;max-height:70dvh;object-fit:contain;margin-block:1rem;margin:auto;max-width: 500px;\\" />\\n<p><em><strong>Note:</strong></em> <em>author of the Rubik\'s cube: <a href=\\"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Rubiks_cube_by_keqs.jpg\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">Lars Karlsson (Keqs)</a>, I added the numbers and arrows.</em></p>\\n<img src=\\"/media/Pythagorean_proof.svg\\" style=\\"display:block;width:100%;height:auto;max-height:70dvh;object-fit:contain;margin-block:1rem;margin:auto;max-width: 500px;\\" />\\n<p><em><strong>Note:</strong></em> <em>here is <a href=\\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=K6qjemwNH6o\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">a video</a> that explains this geometric proof of the Pythagorean theorem in 2 minutes.</em></p>\\n<p>What I want to highlight here is that it takes very few elementary building blocks to construct all human ideas. Starting with a set of \\"elementary experiences\\" and a language to combine them, human beings can construct an infinite number of ideas. This allows them to grasp the invisible and develop all kinds of technology, art, culture, and so on.</p>\\n<p><em>\\"Within our minds, ideas grow like a gigantic coral reef: from a common trunk of universal concepts, multiple branches diverge in every direction. The infinite diversity of cultures stems from the vast combinations of this language of thought.\\"</em><br>\\nStanislas Dehaene, <em>The Rectangle of Lascaux</em> (2026)</p>\\n<p>According to cognitive science, this \\"language of thought\\" is recursive and rests on three basic mental operations: repetition, concatenation, and embedding. That is to say, our mind is capable of developing programs within programs within programs, and each program can repeat a certain number of operations that follow one another.</p>\\n<p><em>\\"The key to these mental programs is the concept of repetition with variation. A circle is a straight line that turns; a spiral is a circle that accelerates…\\"</em><br>\\n<em>The Rectangle of Lascaux</em></p>\\n<p>In this conception of human thought, ideas are like computer programs. This idea may seem absurd at first glance, so let\'s look at an example: how do you teach a computer the concept of a square? Concretely, in a graphics program like Photoshop, how did computer scientists program the software so that the computer can draw a square? The difficulty is that, for a computer, an image of a square is a jumble of pixels with no connection between them.</p>\\n<p>One possibility is the following program:</p>\\n<pre><code>x = length of one side\\nrepeat the following operation 4 times:\\n\\tdraw a line of length x\\n\\trotate 90\xb0\\n</code></pre>\\n<p>Or this one:</p>\\n<pre><code>x = length of one side\\nplace the following points: A(0,0), B(x,0), C(0,x), D(x,x)\\ndraw lines to connect them\\n</code></pre>\\n<img src=\\"/media/carre_points.svg\\" style=\\"display:block;width:100%;height:auto;max-height:70dvh;object-fit:contain;margin-block:1rem;margin:auto;max-width: 300px;\\" />\\n<p>With these programs, the computer can very easily create squares and change their size. When you stretch a square, the computer simply increases the \\"x\\" variable and redraws the lines. And relatively similar programs can be used to recognize basic black-and-white geometric shapes:</p>\\n<pre><code>if the black pixels form a shape with 4 right angles and 4 sides of equal length:\\n\\tit is a square\\nelse:\\n\\tit is not a square\\n</code></pre>\\n<p>Now, let\'s ask ourselves: does the human brain also encode the concept of a square in the form of a program? To answer this question, we can already note one thing: encoding information in the form of a program allows for significant compression of the information and thus makes it easier to memorize. The shorter the program, the easier it will be to memorize this information.</p>\\n<p><em>\\"If the line, the circle, the spiral, and the square are among the simplest and most universal shapes, it is because they correspond to the shortest mental programs our brain is capable of conceiving.\\"</em><br>\\n<em>The Rectangle of Lascaux</em></p>\\n<img src=\\"/media/programme_carre_en.svg\\" style=\\"display:block;width:100%;height:auto;max-height:70dvh;object-fit:contain;margin-block:1rem;margin:auto;\\" />\\n<p>Based on this idea, scientists conducted experiments to see if the size of mental programs predicted the ability to memorize information. And the result is positive:</p>\\n<p><em>\\"Memory errors in adults, like those in children, are predicted by the length of the shortest program capable of reproducing a given sequence—its \\"Kolmogorov complexity\\" [...] The length of the shortest program allows us to predict not only the difficulty of remembering geometric sequences, but also the memory of numbers, the learning of concepts, and many other areas of human psychology. [...] This notion [of the length of the shortest program] is also closely related to the rule that logicians call \\"Ockham\'s razor\\"<sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-17\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-17\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">17</a></sup>.\\"</em><br>\\n<em>The Rectangle of Lascaux</em></p>\\n<p>There is still much to be said and understood about the \\"language of thought\\":</p>\\n<p><em>\\"The neural mechanism of language (or rather, languages) is one of the greatest open questions in contemporary neuroscience.\\"</em><br>\\n<em>The Rectangle of Lascaux</em></p>\\n<p>To explore this question further and discover the latest scientific advances on the subject, I refer you to the book <em>The Rectangle of Lascaux</em>. To conclude this section, let us note one thing: the \\"language of thought\\" seems to be unique to humans. This is notably the hypothesis of Stanislas Dehaene:</p>\\n<p><em>\\"One of the central hypotheses of this book is that recursive language could be the exclusive signature of the human species, as numerous data indicate that other animals are incapable of it.\\"</em><br>\\n<em>The Rectangle of Lascaux</em></p>\\n<p>This idea may seem obvious, but it is less so when we consider that a chick and a bee also possess an innate sense of numbers and space<sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-3\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-3-2\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">3</a></sup>. This brings us to an important question: are \\"elementary experiences\\" universal? We will address this question as it pertains to human beings in the next section.</p>\\n<h2 id=\\"6610f103-1342-42f8-a8d0-2811a560190c\\">The Universality of Human Experience</h2>\\n<p>The purpose of this section is to explain that the \\"elementary experiences\\" of human beings are \\"broadly universal\\". In other words, we all experience life in much the same way, regardless of culture or genetics. Naturally, we don\'t all have exactly the same sensory receptors, nor the same brain, and certainly not the same life. But in reality, we are much more alike than we are different.</p>\\n<p>Concretely, 99% of the population sees colors. Less than 1% is blind, and only 0.0001% sees only shades of gray. The experience of color vision is therefore \\"broadly universal\\". Furthermore, excluding the 4% who are colorblind, \\"normal\\" color vision is universal for 95% of the population.</p>\\n<p>We can generalize this idea by noting that 3 to 7% of the population is affected by \\"dys\\" disorders, such as difficulties with reading and writing (dyslexia), impaired \\"sense of numbers\\" (dyscalculia<sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-18\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-18\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">18</a></sup>), difficulties with spatial orientation (visuospatial dyspraxia), and so on. That said, rather than dwelling on the particularities that set us apart, I believe it is important to note everything that brings us together. Approximately 95% of the population has access to the same basic experiences regarding reading, numbers, spatial perception, color vision, etc. And the 5% who are excluded are only partially so, given that they generally share a multitude of other \\"elementary experiences\\" with the rest of the population, such as emotions, for example.</p>\\n<p>To conclude this section, one thing stands out: sharing \\"elementary experiences\\" is necessary to live in the same reality and to be able to communicate. We will explore this issue in more detail in Chapter 7 when we discuss culture, but I would like to share the fundamental insight here: *if all words refer to human experiences, then human beings must have had similar experiences in order to communicate and understand one another (in addition to having agreed on a common language).</p>\\n<p>With that in mind, let\'s now explore a few \\"inner experiences\\".</p>\\n<h2 id=\\"b3909926-9785-41de-9b44-0f0084c6ee45\\">The Sense of Geometry</h2>\\n<p>Which of the six geometric shapes below is the odd one out?</p>\\n<img src=\\"/media/6_carres.svg\\" style=\\"display:block;width:100%;height:auto;max-height:70dvh;object-fit:contain;margin-block:1rem;margin:auto;max-width: 300px;\\" />\\n<p><em><strong>Note:</strong></em> <em>reproduction of an image from the book The Rectangle of Lascaux.</em></p>\\n<p>You probably figured out that it\'s the shape in the top right corner. But how did you do it? That\'s where \\"sense of geometry\\" comes into play. Just as we perceive colors, we recognize certain geometric shapes innately. Young children and adults with no formal math education have no trouble spotting an irregular quadrilateral among squares. More broadly, all human cultures use the same archetypal shapes in their drawings: squares, rectangles, circles, spirals, parallel lines... And this is significant, because this \\"sense of geometry\\" seems unique to the human species. Other primates, such as baboons, appear to have no sensitivity to geometric shapes<sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-19\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-19\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">19</a></sup>.</p>\\n<p>To give another example, what does the following image represent?</p>\\n<img src=\\"/media/stickman.svg\\" style=\\"display:block;width:100%;height:auto;max-height:70dvh;object-fit:contain;margin-block:1rem;margin:auto;max-width: 80px;\\" />\\n<p>You probably recognized a human figure. Yet it\'s just a few lines. How did you do that? At first, one might think we\'ve simply learned to recognize and draw stick figures this way. But if that\'s the case, how do we explain the figure painted in the Lascaux cave 20,000 years ago?</p>\\n<img src=\\"/media/homme-scene-puit-lascaux.jpg\\" style=\\"display:block;width:100%;height:auto;max-height:70dvh;object-fit:contain;margin-block:1rem;margin:auto;max-width: 600px;\\" />\\n<p>Humans do indeed seem to possess a \\"sense of geometry\\" that allows them to extract the abstract geometric skeleton of the objects they seek to represent. And this \\"sense of geometry\\" seems to become more refined as we grow up:</p>\\n<p><em>\\"Research suggests that it takes until the age of 8 or 10 for a child to fully understand the concept of a right angle, whereas the notion of parallelism develops much earlier, likely as early as 3 or 4 years old. Other properties emerge even earlier: as early as age 1, babies are sensitive to symmetry around a vertical axis.\\"</em><br>\\n<em>The Rectangle of Lascaux</em></p>\\n<p>To explore this question of the sense of geometry further, I refer you once again to Stanislas Dehaene\'s book <em>The Rectangle of Lascaux</em> or, to get started, his lecture series on <a href=\\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=k_ykA1S2J_o&#x26;list=PLOj9pZ2YNGZ_OU2P9oJmTSfviaHf3HYey&#x26;index=48\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\"><em>The Perception of Elementary Mathematical Objects…</em></a>.</p>\\n<h2 id=\\"9c8985b7-0ad5-402a-ba81-0c3c2cc62ddf\\">The Sense of Numbers</h2>\\n<p>Human beings possess a \\"sense of numbers\\" that allows them to:</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li>Distinctly perceive 0, 1, 2, and 3 (or even 4) and compare them (which enables addition and subtraction)</li>\\n<li>Approximate quantities and compare them (something many animals are also capable of)</li>\\n</ul>\\n<p>More formally, quoting Stanislas Dehaene in his book <em>The Number Sense</em> (1996):</p>\\n<p><em>\\"From birth, we have not one but two systems for representing numbers, long before the invention of counting.</em></p>\\n<ul>\\n<li><em>The small-number system, sometimes also called the object-tracking system, represents only sets containing just one, two, or three objects. It allows us to track them precisely, regardless of their path, and provides us with an exact mental model of what happens when we add or remove an object from a small set—thanks to it, we know that one plus one equals exactly two.</em></li>\\n<li><em>The approximate system, on the other hand, can represent any number, large or small. It does not track each object one by one, but estimates their total number. It allows us to compare numbers and combine them using approximate addition and subtraction operations.\\"</em></li>\\n</ul>\\n<p>In practice, in the image below, you immediately perceive the exact number of dots in each box without counting them.</p>\\n<img src=\\"/media/cadre_points_deux.svg\\" style=\\"display:block;width:100%;height:auto;max-height:70dvh;object-fit:contain;margin-block:1rem;margin:auto;max-width: 300px;\\" /> \\n<p><em><strong>Note:</strong></em> <em>reproduction of an image from the book The Number Sense.</em></p>\\n<p>And, in the next one, you immediately notice that there are more dots in some images and you can estimate their number, but you have to count them manually to find out exactly how many there are.</p>\\n<img src=\\"/media/cadre_points_cinq.svg\\" style=\\"display:block;width:100%;height:auto;max-height:70dvh;object-fit:contain;margin-block:1rem;margin:auto;max-width: 300px;\\" />\\n<p><em><strong>Note:</strong></em> <em>reproduction of an image from the book The Number Sense.</em></p>\\n<p>The idea that we can only immediately and accurately perceive quantities up to 3 or 4 can be supported by the symbols used to represent numbers throughout History. Also in <em>The Number Sense</em>:</p>\\n<p><em>\\"Georges Ifrah, in his history of numerical notation, demonstrates that, in the vast majority of civilizations, the first digits are written as in Roman notation by repeating the symbol for one as many times as necessary. However, all civilizations cease to use this method beyond the numbers 3 or 4.\\"</em></p>\\n<img src=\\"/media/evolution_chiffre_en.svg\\" style=\\"display:block;width:100%;height:auto;max-height:70dvh;object-fit:contain;margin-block:1rem;margin:auto;max-width: 500px;\\" />\\n<p><em><strong>Note:</strong></em> <em>reproduction of an image from the book The Number Sense.</em></p>\\n<p>These two \\"sense of numbers\\" correspond to two important concepts in mathematics: the discrete and the continuous. The discrete<sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-20\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-20\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">20</a></sup> deals with distinct values (such as 1, 2, and 3), while the continuous deals with an infinite number of possible values between two points. For example, there are an infinite number of numbers between 0 and 1.</p>\\n<img src=\\"/media/ligne_01.svg\\" style=\\"display:block;width:100%;height:auto;max-height:70dvh;object-fit:contain;margin-block:1rem;margin:auto;max-width: 800px;\\" />\\n<p>And to give a more concrete example:</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li>Continuous approach: water is a fluid that flows</li>\\n<li>Discrete approach: water is composed of particles that push against one another</li>\\n</ul>\\n<p>Our \\"system of small numbers\\" focuses on the discrete, whereas our \\"approximate system\\" focuses on the continuous. The interesting point here is that the ability to perceive the discrete is the basis of language, because to manipulate symbols, one must first be able to grasp them distinctly. More broadly, each of our thoughts is discrete. And it seems that human beings are the only ones capable of perceiving the discrete.</p>\\n<p><em>\\"An abyss separates our species from other animals: we alone seem capable of acquiring discrete, precise, all-or-nothing symbols. Humans have an astonishing predilection for exactness. [...] Two lines are either parallel or they are not.\\"</em><br>\\n<em>The Rectangle of Lascaux</em></p>\\n<p>It is therefore highly likely that the emergence of the ability to manipulate the discrete was a major step in the evolution of consciousness. And this is true even though clearly distinguishing between 1, 2, and 3 seems ridiculously simple to us.</p>\\n<p>To conclude this section, I\'d like to briefly introduce the connection between our sense of numbers and the physical structure of our brain. To do so, let\'s look at an experiment described in <em>The Rectangle of Lascaux</em>:</p>\\n<p><em>\\"The experiment is simple: present a monkey with a cluster of dots, the number of which varies between 1 and 30. [...] Then record the activity of neurons in the dorsolateral prefrontal cortex and the intraparietal sulcus—the very regions that, in our species, become active as soon as we perform even the simplest calculation. You will find a significant proportion of neurons that are interested in the number of objects on the screen. Each cell has its preference: one neuron prefers to see a single object and sees its activity collapse when 2, 3, or more objects are present; another fires vigorously for 2 items, still others for 3, for 4, and so on. Even for large numbers like 30, we continue to find specific neurons. These simply become less and less precise: a neuron that fires for 30 still activates for very close numbers (29, 28, 27…) and ceases to respond only when the ratio between the numbers exceeds 20 or 30% of the preferred value.\\"</em></p>\\n<p>To learn more, I recommend once again that you read <em>The Rectangle of Lascaux</em>. I\'ve only shared here what I needed to support my own ideas. But you\'ll find many other things in it that I haven\'t mentioned here, such as:</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li>The entire experimental section that shed light on the link between the brain\'s capabilities (or our conscious experiences) and what happens physically in the brain</li>\\n<li>The connection between music, mathematics, and language</li>\\n<li>Why all cultures invent imaginary creatures like centaurs or dragons</li>\\n<li>How the brains of rats, flies, or ants contain the equivalent of a map and a compass to navigate space and remember their routes</li>\\n<li>Theories about the evolution of the brain over the last few million years that make humans unique</li>\\n<li>How certain AI models attempt to replicate certain functions of our brain</li>\\n<li>Etc.</li>\\n</ul>\\n<p>That said, the experiments on geometry and numbers were quite abstract; let\'s now look at some much more concrete experiments.</p>\\n<h2 id=\\"c7e32575-b36e-4701-959e-954a18e81684\\">Thinking with One\'s Sex</h2>\\n<p>This title sounds like a joke. Yet it describes a tangible reality: the sexual instinct is a \\"elementary experiences\\" through which we understand the world. We literally think with our sex. To understand this idea, let\'s generalize it. If I talk to you about fighting, fleeing, obeying, cooperating, eating, loving, desiring, etc., you deeply understand what that means, regardless of your culture, because these are instinctive behaviors.</p>\\n<p>To introduce this notion of \\"instinct\\", we can draw a parallel with animals. Birds instinctively know how to build a nest and spiders a web, without having to learn it. The blueprint for construction is encoded in their genes. These relatively complex yet innate behaviors are what we call \\"instinct\\".</p>\\n<p>The important distinction I want to make here is that instinct does not actually determine our behavior, but rather our relationship to the world—that is, our subjective experience of reality. For example, the instinct to fight may have nothing to do with the bloody image we have of war. A doctor may feel as though they are \\"fighting\\" to save lives. The same goes for the farmer who feeds the world or the scientist who advances science. In the same vein, the social instinct that drives us to cooperate allows us just as much to build a peaceful society as it does to organize collectively to wage war against others. This instinct does not determine what we will do with it.</p>\\n<p>There is a key point here that we will discuss again in Chapter 4: what sets humans apart is precisely our ability to master our instincts and sublimate them. For example:</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li>Eating to survive -> gastronomy</li>\\n<li>Copulating to reproduce -> love and sacred sexuality</li>\\n<li>Building a shelter to protect oneself from the cold and rain -> grandiose architecture</li>\\n</ul>\\n<p>What I want to point out is that everything stems from our primal instincts, even the greatest and most beautiful human achievements. To put it simply, if we didn\'t have an instinctive desire to eat, we wouldn\'t be able to understand and taste a good meal. And if we didn\'t have an innate sexual desire, reproduction and sexuality wouldn\'t mean much to us. In other words, it is thanks to the \\"elementary experiences\\" provided by our instincts that we can appreciate the most refined arts. This line of thought leads us to the following idea in Chapter 4: civilizations were not built by suppressing primary instincts, but by sublimating them<sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-21\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-21\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">21</a></sup>.</p>\\n<p>For now, let\'s ask ourselves another question: are our instinctive experiences consistent with reality? For example, feeling hungry and eating actually allows us to survive; this is consistent with reality. The same goes for 1+1=2. And it seems natural that natural selection has shaped our brains so that we are capable of understanding these basic principles. But to what extent does our brain align with reality?</p>\\n<h2 id=\\"86000011-fd5a-44ed-ac0b-1e47a384ae19\\">Psychological Bias: Bug or Feature?</h2>\\n<p>In this section, we will introduce two key concepts: psychological biases and the phenomenon of projection. Let\'s start with the first one.</p>\\n<p>A psychological bias refers to a distorted perception of reality. For example:</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li>Anchoring bias: the first piece of information received strongly influences judgment. Even if it is arbitrary, it serves as a reference point.</li>\\n<li>Confirmation bias: We tend to seek out information that confirms what we already believe. Contradictory information is often ignored or downplayed.</li>\\n<li>Halo effect: a perceived quality of a person influences our judgment of their other characteristics. For example, someone who is attractive may be judged as more competent without evidence.</li>\\n</ul>\\n<p>However, when we talk about psychological bias, we generally assume that the rest of our perceptions are unbiased. Yet all of our \\"elementary experiences\\" give us access only to biased fragments of reality. The best example is that of colors. The experience of seeing colors is an extreme simplification of the electromagnetic spectrum. Colors are already a kind of psychological bias. And this simplification blinds us to certain realities. For example, some birds can see ultraviolet light, and their plumage is actually much more colorful than what we see.</p>\\n<img src=\\"/media/vision_oiseau_en.svg\\" style=\\"display:block;width:100%;height:auto;max-height:70dvh;object-fit:contain;margin-block:1rem;margin:auto;max-width: 700px;\\" />\\n<p><em><strong>Note:</strong></em> <em>I was unable to find the original creator of this image (I added the text). The first instance of this image dates back to 2015 on this site <a href=\\"https://p2praveen.wordpress.com/2015/12/14/what-is-the-use-of-color-vision/\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">p2praveen.wordpress.com</a>. If you are the author and would like me to remove it, please contact me. Please also contact me if you have a replacement image to suggest.</em></p>\\n<p>In fact, this tendency to perceive a simplified version of reality even applies to math:</p>\\n<p><em>\\"The problem of mathematics\' unreasonable effectiveness loses much of its mystery when we keep in mind that mathematical models rarely fit physical reality perfectly. The orbits of the planets are not ellipses, whatever Kepler may have said. [...] In practice, all planets follow chaotic trajectories, impossible to calculate precisely beyond a few thousand years, and which locally resemble ellipses. Similarly, all the laws of physics that we proudly impose on the universe seem to be nothing more than partial models, approximate mental representations that we are constantly refining. [...] Numbers, like all mathematical objects, are mental constructs whose roots lie, in the final analysis, in the human brain\'s adaptation to the regularities of the universe [through natural selection].\\"</em><br>\\n<em>The Number Sense</em></p>\\n<img src=\\"/media/ellipse_theorie_realite_en.svg\\" style=\\"display:block;width:100%;height:auto;max-height:70dvh;object-fit:contain;margin-block:1rem;margin:auto;max-width: 600px;\\" />\\n<p>All of this means one thing: the first \\"psychological biases\\" stem from the way we perceive reality. They are not bugs, but features<sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-22\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-22\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">22</a></sup>. For, indeed, while math and colors are biased simplifications, these simplifications are useful and effective, particularly in terms of energy efficiency<sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-23\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-23\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">23</a></sup>. It is no coincidence that most animals see colors and are capable of estimating quantities. Natural selection favored these \\"senses\\" because they increased an individual\'s chances of survival at a very low energy cost (compared, for example, to larger muscles requiring more energy).</p>\\n<p>The same applies to love, combat, cooperation, or the desire to eat. These are simplifications of reality, but they are useful and effective in practice. Thus, viewing a relationship through the lens of love or a situation through the lens of combat can be useful, but using this \\"framework\\" rather than another is already a bias.</p>\\n<p>This bias can manifest itself, in particular, as what is known as \\"projection\\": the projection of one\'s \\"inner experience\\" onto the world<sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-24\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-24\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">24</a></sup>. Concretely, a person who realizes they are in the \\"friend zone\\"<sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-25\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-25\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">25</a></sup> discovers that they were projecting their own feelings onto the other person, without realizing that those feelings were not reciprocated. Similarly, if you\'re angry and feel like fighting, you may perceive conflicts where none exist. For example, you might interpret others\' words and actions as attacks against you, when in fact they are not.</p>\\n<p><em>\\"If the only tool you have is a hammer, you might tend to view every problem as a nail.\\"</em><br>\\nAbraham Maslow (psychologist known in particular for the \\"<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maslow%27s_hierarchy_of_needs\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">Maslow\'s hierarchy of needs\\" </a>, a hierarchical representation of human needs, derived from his work on human motivation)</p>\\n<p>That said, sometimes other people\'s words or actions are actually veiled attacks, and fighting back isn\'t necessarily a bad choice. However, to be able to say that, you still need to be aware of alternative interpretations. And becoming aware of these alternatives is by no means easy. In fact, this is one of the hallmarks of intelligence: the ability to apply multiple frameworks of understanding to a single situation. That is, the ability to perceive the multiple dimensions of a situation in order to access a higher level of detail<sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-26\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-26\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">26</a></sup>. \\"Accessing a new dimension\\" can be interpreted as: \\"looking at something from a different perspective...\\"</p>\\n<p>This concept of dimension is fundamental, so I\'ll take a moment to explain it to you. This will then allow us to see how our brain constructs multidimensional experiences from our \\"elementary experiences\\".</p>\\n<h2 id=\\"f9901c06-e2a5-41fb-b061-a053704021a5\\">Understanding Dimensions</h2>\\n<p>In this section, we will introduce an essential concept: dimensions. I want to dedicate a section to this because it is an extremely powerful idea for understanding reality (see <em>The Power of Ideas</em>). And I will use it frequently going forward.</p>\\n<img src=\\"/media/dimensions.svg\\" style=\\"display:block;width:100%;height:auto;max-height:70dvh;object-fit:contain;margin-block:1rem;margin:auto;max-width: 400px;\\" />\\n<p>This concept of dimension can be applied to anything. Every object in the world around us can be understood through multiple dimensions. For example, we perceive every person around us as a multidimensional object<sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-27\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-27\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">27</a></sup>, with a dimension for:</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li>Height</li>\\n<li>Weight</li>\\n<li>Age</li>\\n<li>Etc.</li>\\n</ul>\\n<img src=\\"/media/ex_taille_dimensions_en.svg\\" style=\\"display:block;width:100%;height:auto;max-height:70dvh;object-fit:contain;margin-block:1rem;margin:auto;max-width: 450px;\\" />\\n<p>It is not possible to represent more than 3 dimensions geometrically. But we can use tricks such as a color dimension (the following example is in 2 dimensions + a grayscale dimension).</p>\\n<img src=\\"/media/ex_dimension_couleur_en.svg\\" style=\\"display:block;width:100%;height:auto;max-height:70dvh;object-fit:contain;margin-block:1rem;margin:auto;max-width: 500px;\\" />\\n<p>That said, just because we cannot visually represent more than 3 dimensions does not mean we cannot create spaces with more than 3 dimensions and perform calculations on them. For example, in ChatGPT\'s artificial intelligence model, each word is an object with over 4,000 dimensions. What does a space with 4,000 dimensions look like? We\'ll see that in a moment. Before that, let\'s connect the concept of dimension to human experience.</p>\\n<h2 id=\\"353eeefd-3d64-4f82-ae67-34cb07fdbddc\\">Multidimensional Experience</h2>\\n<p>The goal of this section is to introduce the following idea: <em>our elementary senses allow us to perceive multiple dimensions of reality.</em></p>\\n<p>To introduce this idea, let\'s take the example of temperature to link the concept of dimension to human experience: feeling a temperature means experiencing the dimension of temperature. This means:</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li>Being able to perceive the dimension of temperature (i.e. having sensory receptors that allow us to feel temperature)</li>\\n<li>Measuring within this dimension, that is, assessing the temperature (each receptor sends a specific value to the brain)</li>\\n<li>Weighing the values from all these sensors to determine an overall composite value (we have approximately 200,000 temperature sensors distributed throughout the body, and when we sense a temperature, we are only concerned with a composite of the temperature of a specific part of our body, such as the feet)</li>\\n</ul>\\n<img src=\\"/media/dimension_thermometre_en.svg\\" style=\\"display:block;width:100%;height:auto;max-height:70dvh;object-fit:contain;margin-block:1rem;margin:auto;max-width: 500px;\\" />\\n<p>Temperature is an easy example because it is a human experience that can be represented in a single dimension. However, most experiences are more complex because they are multidimensional. To illustrate this, let\'s take the example of colors: what appears to us as the color dimension is actually based on three dimensions (excluding color blindness). To simplify slightly (see <a href=\\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FvbNrwjIrNU\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">this video</a> for details), our eyes process the light they receive using three types of cones:</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li>Red cones measure the intensity of red in the incoming light (red dimension)</li>\\n<li>Green cones do the same for green (green dimension)</li>\\n<li>Blue cones do the same for blue (blue dimension)</li>\\n</ul>\\n<img src=\\"/media/dimension_daltonien_en.svg\\" style=\\"display:block;width:100%;height:auto;max-height:70dvh;object-fit:contain;margin-block:1rem;margin:auto;max-width: 300px;\\" />\\n<img src=\\"/media/RGBCube_a.svg\\" style=\\"display:block;width:100%;height:auto;max-height:70dvh;object-fit:contain;margin-block:1rem;margin:auto;max-width: 400px;\\" />\\n<p><em><strong>Note:</strong></em> <em>3-dimensional representation of colors (author: <a href=\\"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:RGBCube_a.svg\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">SharkD</a>). Note that there are other ways to represent colors. To learn more about \\"color geometry\\", watch <a href=\\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7KYwi2F5Ce4\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">the video from the ScienceClic channel</a> on the subject.</em></p>\\n<p>To explain how our eyes create the experience of color, I\'m going to use an analogy based on how modern screens work. The basic principle is essentially the same, but it\'s easier to explain.</p>\\n<p>Your computer screen is made up of pixels. If your screen\'s resolution is 1920x1080, that means it contains 1920x1080 = 2,073,600 pixels. Each of these pixels contains three small lights called \\"subpixels\\": one red, one green, and one blue.</p>\\n<img src=\\"/media/pixel.jpg\\" style=\\"display:block;width:100%;height:auto;max-height:70dvh;object-fit:contain;margin-block:1rem;margin:auto;max-width: 400px;\\" />\\n<p><em><strong>Note:</strong></em> <em>image by <a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Closeup_of_pixels.JPG\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">Kprateek88</a></em></p>\\n<p>The color of the pixel varies depending on the intensity of each of these lights. All colors can be produced by adjusting the brightness of these three subpixels, through <a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Additive_color\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">additive color mixing</a>.</p>\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n<table><thead><tr><th>Subpixels</th><th>Pixel color</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Red, green, and blue at maximum brightness</td><td>White</td></tr><tr><td>Red, green, and blue off</td><td>Black</td></tr><tr><td>Only red is on</td><td>Red</td></tr><tr><td>Only green is on</td><td>Green</td></tr><tr><td>Only blue is on</td><td>Blue</td></tr><tr><td>Red and green on, blue off</td><td>Yellow</td></tr></tbody></table>\\n<p>That being said, we can observe two things:</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li>It is not possible to see the world solely in shades of red</li>\\n<li>We do not have a sensor for the color yellow, and yet we see it</li>\\n</ul>\\n<p>In other words, we do not see the colors or light waves that our eyes capture. The colors we see are always the result of at least one additional processing step. We see yellow when our red and green cones are stimulated, but not the blue ones. In the same way that a pixel displays yellow by lighting up only its red and green subpixels.</p>\\n<img src=\\"/media/capteur_inconscient_xp_en.svg\\" style=\\"display:block;width:100%;height:auto;max-height:70dvh;object-fit:contain;margin-block:1rem;margin:auto;max-width: 800px;\\" />\\n<p>More broadly, our experience of reality does not depend solely on our sensory receptors. What we see is always an interpretation made by our brain based on the data sent by our senses. Our conscious experience is always the result of significant unconscious processing. Once again, optical illusions clearly illustrate this principle. Let\'s recall the one already presented. As a reminder, boxes A and B are the same color in the following image:</p>\\n<a href=\\"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:grey_square_optical_illusion.svg\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">\\n<img src=\\"/media/grey_square_optical_illusion.svg\\" style=\\"display:block;width:100%;height:auto;max-height:70dvh;object-fit:contain;margin-block:1rem;margin:auto;max-width: 500px;\\" />\\n</a>\\n<p>Finally, we might ask ourselves: if a shadow can influence our perception of colors, can a sound alter our sense of taste, or can the sight of a face influence our perception of a sound? And how does our brain make connections between very different experiences to allow us to think things like, \\"a rise in temperature is like an increase in a number\\"?</p>\\n<h2 id=\\"9b3c3fd7-826a-4b05-a0a8-4924078e8b27\\">Hearing Colors and Counting Space</h2>\\n<p>The goal of this section is to present the following idea: <em>synesthesia allows us to connect the multiple dimensions we perceive to create a multidimensional image of reality.</em></p>\\n<p>To begin with, let\'s recall what the previous optical illusion highlights: a shadow can influence our perception of colors. This means one thing: in terms of our subjective experience, \\"elementary experiences\\" are not independent. Every subjective experience is multidimensional. The perception of colors is not independent of our instinctive understanding of shadows. Similarly, visual perception can alter the perception of a sound (watch <a href=\\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aFPtc8BVdJk\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">this video</a> of the McGurk effect). And sight, touch, sound, emotions, etc., can greatly influence taste<sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-28\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-28\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">28</a></sup>. Thus, every subjective experience is always multidimensional. Scientists refer to <a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multisensory_integration\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">\\"multisensory integration\\"</a> or <a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crossmodal\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">\\"cross-modal perception\\"</a> to describe how the human brain constructs a \\"perception\\" or a \\"subjective experience\\" from the multiple pieces of information it receives from the senses.</p>\\n<p>Now, while our subjective experience is always multidimensional, we are nevertheless quite capable of distinguishing \\"elementary experiences\\" such as colors independently. For example, if you look around you, you\'ll first see a general picture. But you can take the time to distinguish colors, geometric shapes, and objects. In other words, even though these subjective experiences are multidimensional, we\'re generally able to distinguish the dimensions that make them up. This is what scientists call \\"selective attention\\".</p>\\n<p>That said, you might have an objection. Indeed, in certain altered states of consciousness, some people report seeing sounds, hearing colors, or tasting words. This blending of perceptions is also found in some individuals in their normal state. They are called \\"synesthetes.\\" The brains of these individuals may, for example, instinctively associate colors with letters or sounds.</p>\\n<a href=\\"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Synesthesia.svg\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">\\n<img src=\\"/media/synesthesia.svg\\" style=\\"display:block;width:100%;height:auto;max-height:70dvh;object-fit:contain;margin-block:1rem;margin:auto;max-width: 500px;\\" />\\n</a>\\n<p>However, in both cases, the individual remains capable of breaking down their perception. Those who hear colors are able to distinguish color on one level and sound on another. Just as you and I are able to distinguish color and geometric shapes in an image. In other words, we are all synesthetes. We only notice those whose synesthesia—that is, whose associations—are unusual.</p>\\n<p>More broadly, synesthesia (or the \\"cross-modality\\" of subjective experience) is the foundation of human intelligence (and, for now, part of its superiority over AI<sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-29\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-29\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">29</a></sup>). Each sensory receptor allows us to perceive a dimension of reality. And synesthesia allows us to connect these perceptions to create a multidimensional image of reality. That is, to reconstruct a complete image of the elephant from the descriptions of the blind men, to borrow from the Indian fable:</p>\\n<img src=\\"/media/aveugles_elephant.jpg\\" style=\\"display:block;width:100%;height:auto;max-height:70dvh;object-fit:contain;margin-block:1rem;margin:auto;max-width: 700px;\\" />\\n<p><em>\\"The Blind Men and the Elephant tells the story of several blind men who encounter an elephant for the first time by touching it. Each touches a different part (the trunk, the leg, the tail…) and draws a different conclusion about what the animal is: a snake, a pillar, a rope, etc. Since they perceive only a part of reality, they argue, each believing they are right. The moral of the story is that truth can be multifaceted and partial depending on one\'s perspective, and that we must bring together these perceptions to understand the whole.\\"</em></p>\\n<p>Given that an elephant potentially has an infinite number of dimensions, the more dimensions your mental representation of the elephant includes, the more accurate it will be to reality. The same applies to a human being. The more dimensions you know about them—such as their height, weight, age, occupation, etc.—the better you know them.</p>\\n<p>Furthermore, synesthesia is necessary for recognizing and understanding analogies such as: \\"a rise in temperature is like an increase in a number\\". It is through synesthesia that we can form ideas by making connections between our \\"elementary experiences\\" and perceive a single reality underlying different experiences.</p>\\n<p>For example, we naturally make a connection between the dimension of quantities and the dimension of space. The idea that numbers measure space is innate and manifests itself in the experience of the \\"number line\\". Instinctively, we visualize quantities as a line oriented from left to right (a phenomenon that appears to be shared by chicks from birth and other animals<sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-30\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-30\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">30</a></sup>).</p>\\n<img src=\\"/media/ligne_numerique.svg\\" style=\\"display:block;width:100%;height:auto;max-height:70dvh;object-fit:contain;margin-block:1rem;margin:auto;max-width: 800px;\\" />\\n<p><em>\\"Tout se passe effectivement comme si les diff\xe9rents nombres \xe9taient align\xe9s mentalement sur une ligne o\xf9 chaque position correspond \xe0 une certaine quantit\xe9. Des nombres proches sont repr\xe9sent\xe9s par des positions proches sur la ligne. Rien d\'\xe9tonnant donc \xe0 ce qu\'on les confonde plus facilement, ce que refl\xe8te l\'effet de distance num\xe9rique.\\"</em><br>\\n<em>The Number Sense</em></p>\\n<p><em>\\"It is as if the different numbers were mentally aligned on a line where each position corresponds to a certain quantity. Numbers that are close to each other are represented by positions close to each other on the line. It is therefore not surprising that we confuse them more easily, which is reflected in the numerical distance effect.\\"</em><br>\\n<em>The Number Sense</em></p>\\n<p>To illustrate the second part of this quote, try to determine which is the larger number between:</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li>1576 and 1569</li>\\n<li>1576 and 89,038</li>\\n</ul>\\n<p>Clearly, it is much easier to compare 1576 and 89,038 roughly than 1576 and 1569. And this can be explained by the distance between them on our number line.</p>\\n<p>That said, scientists have noticed something curious: our representation of quantities is not linear, but logarithmic. To illustrate this, try placing 1 million on the following line:</p>\\n<img src=\\"/media/ligne_numerique_milliard_en.svg\\" style=\\"display:block;width:100%;height:auto;max-height:70dvh;object-fit:contain;margin-block:1rem;margin:auto;max-width: 800px;\\" />\\n<p>Instinctively, you might be tempted to answer: \\"not far from the middle\\". But in reality, 1 million is very close to 1,000 on this line: a thousand times closer to 1,000 than to 1 billion. The interesting thing is that by realizing this, your spatial representation of quantities has become more precise. Because our number line can actually change. For example, among young children and adults who have received no mathematical education, this logarithmic distortion is even present for small numbers. For them, it is the number 3 that lies between 1 and 9, not 5. In other words, by default, our number line looks like the following image, but mathematical education allows us to refine it.</p>\\n<img src=\\"/media/ligne_numerique_log.svg\\" style=\\"display:block;width:100%;height:auto;max-height:70dvh;object-fit:contain;margin-block:1rem;margin:auto;max-width: 800px;\\" />\\n<p>For reference, here is the difference in shape between a linear and a logarithmic curve:</p>\\n<img src=\\"/media/log_lineairet_en.svg\\" style=\\"display:block;width:100%;height:auto;max-height:70dvh;object-fit:contain;margin-block:1rem;margin:auto;max-width: 700px;\\" />\\n<p>Well, we\'ve just seen the connection between the concept of dimension and human experience, as well as how we perceive dimensions and can connect them. Now let\'s see how it\'s possible to access spaces with more than three dimensions.</p>\\n<h2 id=\\"dcc438bc-6788-400a-8ceb-ec2df503244c\\">Beyond the 3<sup>rd</sup> dimension</h2>\\n<p>The goal of this section is to show how language allows us to access abstract realities that go beyond our \\"inner experiences\\". For example, how we can access spaces with more than three dimensions that are beyond our visual perception.</p>\\n<p>To make this concrete, let\'s look at a short exercise. If I ask you to rotate a line a quarter turn to the right, you should be able to do so without much difficulty in 2 and 3 dimensions. But if I ask you to do the same thing in a 50-dimensional space, you probably won\'t be able to. Why?</p>\\n<img src=\\"/media/2_3_50D.svg\\" style=\\"display:block;width:100%;height:auto;max-height:70dvh;object-fit:contain;margin-block:1rem;margin:auto;max-width: 500px;\\" />\\n<p>Answer: because our innate perception and sense of geometry allow us to see and reason only in a space with a maximum of three dimensions. As a result, beyond three dimensions, we are unable to solve problems visually.</p>\\n<p>Yet mathematicians have no trouble working with 50-dimensional spaces and creating AIs like ChatGPT with over 4,000 dimensions. But the truth is that, throughout human history, no mathematician has ever seen a space with more than three dimensions. They have all simply accepted to study reality by using symbols as a blind man\'s cane.</p>\\n<p><em>\\"In geometry, what is essential is invisible to the eye; one sees well only with the mind.\\"</em><br>\\nEmmanuel Giroux (blind mathematician), paraphrasing <em>The Little Prince</em><sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-31\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-31\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">31</a></sup> by Antoine de Saint-Exup\xe9ry</p>\\n<p><em>\\"Young man, in mathematics, you don\'t understand things. You just get used to them.\\"</em><br>\\nJohn von Neumann (mathematician and physicist who helped create the first atomic bomb, founded quantum mechanics, and laid the foundations for modern computers)</p>\\n<p>The foundation of science lies in giving up on clearly perceiving what cannot be perceived even with the sharpest of the senses, such as sight, and instead trusting in symbols: if the equations are correct, then it must be true and exist. Fundamentally, our only means of accessing spaces with 50 dimensions is language.</p>\\n<p>However, the language in question is not arbitrary. Mathematical symbols are all based on our \\"elementary experiences\\". To access a 50-dimensional space, we must first be able to perfectly describe a 3-dimensional space using symbols and equations. And we verify these symbols and equations through sight and our sense of geometry. From there, if an equation works for 1, 2, and 3 dimensions and we know how to create dimensions, then we can create as many as we want and perform calculations on them.</p>\\n<img src=\\"/media/2_3_50D_algebreai.svg\\" style=\\"display:block;width:100%;height:auto;max-height:70dvh;object-fit:contain;margin-block:1rem;margin:auto;max-width: 500px;\\" />\\n<p><em><strong>Note:</strong></em> <em>this image illustrates the position of point A in 2D, 3D, and 50D spaces. \\"A(1,1,0)\\" means that point A is located at coordinates 1 on the x-axis, 1 on the y-axis, and 0 on the z-axis (depicting the z-axis is difficult since the book page is 2D). x, y, and z are variables that represent a number (a variable is a kind of \\"number box\\" that can be manipulated without knowing the number inside). Each dimension is defined by an axis. So to add a dimension, you simply add an axis. Generally, we call the axis of the 1<sup>st</sup> dimension \\"x\\", the axis of the 2<sup>nd</sup> \\"y\\", and the axis of the 3<sup>rd</sup> \\"z\\", but this is arbitrary. In the last box on the right, I could have written A(a,b,c,d,e,f,...) or A(x1,x2,x3,x4,...,x50). To go further, the best video series I know on the subject is the one from the YouTube channel 3Blue1Brown: <a href=\\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fNk_zzaMoSs&#x26;list=PLZHQObOWTQDPD3MizzM2xVFitgF8hE_ab&#x26;index=1\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">The Essence of Linear Algebra</a>.</em></p>\\n<p>The key point here is that to understand a 50-dimensional space, you must first understand geometrically what a dimension is (something that blind people are capable of) and then know how to represent it using mathematical symbols. What I want to emphasize here is that purely abstract ideas do not exist. If something seems completely abstract to you, it\'s simply because you can\'t connect it to an experience you\'ve had. And, more broadly, if an equation describes a situation that seems impossible to you visually or logically, there is certainly a problem in the equation or in the system of symbols used.</p>\\n<p><em>\\"The mathematical approach is one of integrity and alignment with oneself. [...] I have stopped believing that there are things that are counterintuitive by nature. The things presented to us as \\"counterintuitive\\" or \\"paradoxical\\" are either false or poorly explained.\\"</em><br>\\nDavid Bessis (mathematician and entrepreneur), in <em>Mathematica (2022)</em></p>\\n<p><em>\\"There is no mathematical object that cannot be made intuitive by visualizing it in pictorial form<sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-32\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-32\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">32</a></sup>. [...] There is nothing in mathematics that cannot be conceived in simpler terms, for all mathematical objects arise from a recomposition of prior ideas.\\"</em><br>\\n<em>The Rectangle of Lascaux</em></p>\\n<p>This idea can be summarized as follows: <em>the best way to understand an idea is to experience it through an elementary sense. More broadly, the only way to understand something is to connect it to an experience we have had<sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-33\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-33\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">33</a></sup>.</em></p>\\n<p>Here is a relevant quote to illustrate this idea:</p>\\n<p><em>\\"You can understand any mathematical concept [and this applies to other fields] in six ways: verbal, visual, algebraic, numerical, computational, and historical.</em></p>\\n<ol>\\n<li><em>Verbal—explain in words</em></li>\\n<li><em>Visual—make a graph</em></li>\\n<li><em>Algebraic—write the equation</em></li>\\n<li><em>Numerical—do a numerical example</em></li>\\n<li><em>Computational—code a solver or algorithm</em></li>\\n<li><em>Historical—tell where it came from\\"</em><br>\\nBalaji Srinivasan (entrepreneur and intellectual), in <a href=\\"https://balajianthology.com/\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\"><em>The Anthology of Balaji</em></a> (compiled and edited by <a href=\\"https://www.ejorgenson.com/\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">Eric Jorgenson</a>)</li>\\n</ol>\\n<p>This idea is fundamental, and the example of geometric dimensions may have seemed a bit too theoretical to you. So let\'s now try to understand how we grasp more common abstract concepts, such as that of a \\"state\\".</p>\\n<h2 id=\\"4f7df581-daec-46f6-bb26-044096993b3b\\">Understanding History Through War Stories</h2>\\n<p>The goal of this section is to illustrate the following insight with examples: <em>the only way to understand something is to connect it to an experience we have had.</em></p>\\n<p>How did you first learn about France? Probably visually, through a map<sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-34\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-34\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">34</a></sup>. Or perhaps, while traveling, you discovered that some people spoke a particular language and that there was a geographical community where those people lived, sharing, more broadly, a specific culture. France would then be, for you, the place where people speak French and live the French way. And you certainly have other experiences that taught you about France. Once again, the way you conceive of \\"France\\" is directly linked to the experiences you\'ve had in connection with this concept.</p>\\n<p>We can take this further: how does a child discover the existence of society and the state? Answer: by discovering these words and their definitions. For language serves not only to name, but also to conceive. The only way to conceive of a 50-dimensional space is to use language, and the same is true for a society and a state. Notably because to understand what a society or a state is, one must give up hope of seeing them in real life. You will never actually see what <a href=\\"https://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%89tat\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">Wikipedia describes regarding a state</a>:</p>\\n<p><em>\\"A state is a geographically defined human community with a centralized political organization consisting of institutions responsible for formulating, enforcing, and upholding a set of rules.\\"</em></p>\\n<p>At best, you might picture a map of your country, a small crowd, a few public buildings, or a law book, but you will never actually see a state. Nevertheless, learning the concept of the state truly gives you access to a concrete and useful reality. Just as spaces with more than three dimensions enable the creation of AIs like ChatGPT, the concept of the state truly helps us understand and manage the world.</p>\\n<p>More broadly, concepts allow us to access a higher level of detail in reality. To understand a subject, it is generally enough to grasp its major concepts and the connections between them. Consequently, one of the main goals of education is to successfully introduce concepts—that is, powerful, concise, and useful ideas that enable us to understand and master what lies beyond our most obvious senses, such as sight.</p>\\n<p>Ideally, these courses draw on a wide range of experiences to illustrate their concepts</p>\\n<p>For example, History classes provide an opportunity to introduce concepts such as: society, state, territory, economy, civilization, chronology, nation, revolution, resistance, industry, globalization, etc. And, ideally, these classes draw on a wide range of experiences to present them: maps, statistics, diagrams, narratives of battles, accounts of people\'s lives, etc. Once again, the more experiences we can link to a concept, the better we understand and remember it. Because: <em>the only way to understand something is to connect it to an experience we\'ve had</em>.</p>\\n<p>The idea of learning History by reading \\"accounts of battles or human life stories\\" might seem a bit ridiculous at first glance. But I want to emphasize this point: one cannot understand a human society or a historical period without having an idea of what the people who lived through it actually experienced. For example, one cannot understand World War I without having read an autobiographical account by a soldier on the front lines, such as <em>Storm of Steel</em> by Ernst J\xfcnger. What I want to point out here is that stories (and \\"storytelling\\") should not be viewed as a means of capturing or maintaining the attention of students or readers, but rather as an extremely rich source of information<sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-35\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-35\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">35</a></sup>.</p>\\n<p>Understanding what a soldier on the front lines might have felt is essential to understanding how the elementary particles of human history—human beings—behave. Human psychology is the equivalent of the physical laws that govern the behavior of particles in matter. And, unfortunately, humans are very poor at predicting their own behavior in situations they have never experienced. For example, even when very well prepared, soldiers tend to apply only 10 to 20% of what they have learned in real-life situations, on average<sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-24\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-24-2\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">24</a></sup>. And humans are even worse at predicting the behavior of other humans they know only from a distance. Hence the practical utility of literary and cultural studies:</p>\\n<p><em>\\"The curiosity of the early orientalists was practical, for the process of colonization went more smoothly when the colonizers could understand the language, culture, and world views of their subject peoples.\\"</em><br>\\nJoscelyn Godwin (musicologist and historian of esotericism), in <em>The Theosophical Enlightenment</em> (1994)</p>\\n<p>A long time ago, I heard something along the lines of: \\"Autobiographical texts are always more useful for understanding a historical period than sociological studies by academics.\\" While this idea isn\'t entirely impartial or accurate, I find it interesting and worth sharing with you.</p>\\n<p>To wrap up this section, one thing stands out: it seems a bit childish and ridiculous to read stories to learn History or to need concrete examples to understand something. The paradox is that concrete examples are the only way to truly understand something. More broadly:</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li>We may feel insulted if the examples and words used in an explanation are too simple or concrete (when, on the contrary, this is the best way to understand<sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-36\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-36\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">36</a></sup>)</li>\\n<li>The harder a speech is to understand, the more interesting and important it seems, which is not really relevant (this explains why intellectuals are inclined to use language that is difficult to understand, for example, by using complicated and rare words that few people will understand)</li>\\n<li>We can prefer to feel intelligent rather than actually understand something or find solutions (which results in \\"over-intellectualization\\": instead of solving important problems that are easy to understand, we may seek to solve complicated problems that are not important)</li>\\n</ul>\\n<p>These issues run deeper than they appear and highlight a tension between appearances and reality. This leads us to a question: if our only means of accessing what lies beyond our elementary senses is to use symbols, how can we avoid being biased by those symbols? That is to say, by appearances? More broadly, do we see anything other than symbols?</p>\\n<h2 id=\\"dc541ca7-06fe-4176-9798-e8ad1563f21f\\">Appearance vs. Reality, or the Prison of Symbols</h2>\\n<p><em>\\"Everything in this world we see relates to another world we do not see […] for we live, in fact, amidst a system of invisible things manifested visibly.\\"</em><br>\\nJoseph de Maistre (politician and philosopher), in <em>St. Petersburg Dialogues</em> (1821)</p>\\n<p>The purpose of this section is to present the following idea: <em>if human beings can only grasp the abstract through symbols, then these symbols shape their perceptions. In other words, when we go beyond the limits of elementary senses such as sight or geometry, we never see reality itself, but only symbols that are supposed to indicate the presence of that reality. And these symbols can mislead us.</em></p>\\n<p>To illustrate this idea, let\'s take an example: how do you know if someone is intelligent or not? First, we can note that \\"intelligence\\" is an abstract concept. Therefore, our definition of intelligence is shaped by the experiences we\'ve had related to this concept. Concretely, your definition of intelligence will not be the same if you became a civil servant after 8 years of study or if, on the contrary, you dropped out of school at 16 and held various jobs before starting a business. In exactly the same way, if you studied philosophy for 8 years, your definition of intelligence will be very different from that of an engineer, a farmer, or a soldier.</p>\\n<p>The key point here is that all these differences in experience will not only change the words you use to define intelligence, but also—and above all—your conception of what intelligence is and what an intelligent person is. This will lead to radically different answers to the question: \\"How do you know if someone is intelligent or not?\\"</p>\\n<p>To illustrate this, I\'m going to share a slightly ridiculous anecdote from my youth. I was walking down the street with a girl whose intelligence I valued. At one point, as we walked past a nail salon, I said to her, \\"One really has to be stupid to go to a place like that.\\" She then looked me in the eye and replied, \\"You know, I actually like it.\\" I then realized that intelligence had very little to do with whether or not you like manicures.</p>\\n<p>Before this experience, if someone had asked me: \\"How do you know if someone is intelligent or not?\\" I might have answered, \\"If someone likes manicures, they\'re not intelligent.\\" Because \\"liking manicures\\" was a symbol of stupidity in my mind. In the same way that winning a Nobel Prize was a symbol of intelligence. And this brings us to the important point: my perception of intelligence was shaped by a set of symbols of intelligence and stupidity.</p>\\n<p>And it still is, for that matter. Because, to perceive abstract realities like intelligence, we have no choice but to rely on symbols. Whether it\'s a diploma, a rank, a physical appearance (white coat, suit and tie...), a way of speaking (clear articulation and rich vocabulary), an outcome (achievement, artwork, medal, money, etc.), and so on. More broadly, we learn what intelligence is through our life experiences, by identifying recurring symbols associated with or opposed to intelligence. Consequently, these symbols shape our perception of intelligence.</p>\\n<p>We can generalize what has just been said. For example, we never directly perceive wealth or happiness. We can only perceive symbols that are supposed to indicate their presence. For example, a nice car for wealth and a smile for happiness. And these symbols can be misleading. Some people go into debt and eat pasta every day just to drive a nice car. And those who are always smiling in their social media photos are sometimes depressed in reality.</p>\\n<p>This idea of symbols may seem a bit theoretical, and yet it entirely determines the reality in which we live. We believe we see abstract realities, but we see only systems of symbols that make sense to us. The best example is that of ideologies. From the outside, they may seem absurd. But for those who adhere to them, they make sense. Words and symbols describe abstract realities that exist in the eyes of activists, just as intelligence, wealth, happiness, or a 50-dimensional space do.</p>\\n<p>This idea deserves to be illustrated. That is what we will do in the next section by discussing politics.</p>\\n<h2 id=\\"abc2140e-6918-41ab-992d-2289a4809d3f\\">From Experience to Politics</h2>\\n<p>The aim of this section is to present the following idea: <em>Our representation of the world and the symbols we use to describe it are shaped by the experiences we have had. So much so that our ideas and opinions are an expression of our lived experiences. Very often, \\"thinking\\" simply consists of putting our experiences into words.</em></p>\\n<p>Let\'s dive right into the heart of the matter with a political example. We tend to take ourselves very seriously and believe that what we think is the result of long and serious reflection. Yet much of what we think and believe is merely the consequence of our life experiences. Political convictions clearly illustrate this reality.</p>\\n<p>We can broadly summarize the political landscape in France (and probably in much of the West) between 1900 and 2000 as follows:</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li>Blue-collar workers are far-left</li>\\n<li>Civil servants are left-wing</li>\\n<li>Self-employed workers (including some entrepreneurs, artisans, and farmers with a small amount of land) are far-right</li>\\n<li>Business owners and annuitant are right-wing</li>\\n</ul>\\n<p>If we try to be impartial, we can roughly summarize everyone\'s political views with a simple question: \\"How can I live better given my economic and social situation?\\"</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li>For workers, the goal is to capture a larger share of the wealth produced in their companies, which means raising wages</li>\\n<li>For civil servants and all those who live off public funds, the goal is to secure more public money, which often involves raising taxes</li>\\n<li>For the self-employed, the goal is to protect themselves from the predatory practices of large corporations and pay less in taxes, while taking full advantage of public services</li>\\n<li>For business owners and annuitant, the goal is to give less money to workers and the state and to secure a monopoly on markets by devouring independent businesses (thus capturing ever-greater market share and an ever-larger portion of the wealth produced by their companies or properties, while redistributing as little as possible)</li>\\n</ul>\\n<p>Given this observation, one might conclude that people rationally choose their political views based on their own interests. However, this interpretation obscures a fundamental reality: most of us are convinced that our political views are universally correct and not biased by our personal interests. And we believe that it is others who are mistaken, unfair, and have not made the effort to reflect or question themselves.</p>\\n<p>This paradox can be resolved by applying everything we\'ve discussed in this chapter: most differences in political views do not stem from differences between individuals, but from differences in our life experiences (there appears to be a broadly universal \\"sense of justice;\\" only 1 to 4% of the population is psychopathic and may not share it). Concretely, when a factory worker left the factory after a 14-hour shift in 1900, he might have felt a sense of injustice toward his boss and \\"capitalists\\" in general.</p>\\n<p><em>\\"Workers of the new dyehouse! For 14 and a quarter hours of work a day, immersed from head to toe in the deadly fumes of the dye, you now earn only 12 rubles a month. Consider our demands: we also want to put an end to the illegal deductions from your wages due to your foreman\'s incompetence.\\"</em><br>\\nLenin (revolutionary and 1<sup>er</sup> leader of the USSR), in <em>To the Workers of the Thornton Factory</em> (1895)</p>\\n<p>However, when, after his 14-hour workday, the 20th-century worker publicly expressed his political views, he was not presenting a thesis on society\'s economic and social situation. He was simply expressing the injustice he experienced. He was putting his experience into words. And that is precisely what we all do. We experience injustices or other situations, and we put them into words. Absolutely no one escapes it. From the bottom to the top of society, we are all prisoners of our experience and the symbols we use to express it. And what we call \\"thinking\\" is very often limited to verbalizing our experience or our lived reality. This applies even to scientific discoveries. An \\"eureka\\" moment is the verbalization of an intuition resulting from a long period of unconscious work or a new observation<sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-37\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-37\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">37</a></sup>.</p>\\n<p>We will explore how to master one\'s mind to \\"gain freedom\\" in Chapter 5. For now, let\'s ask a question: Do some people have more meaningful experiences than others and are better at articulating those experiences? Put another way, do some people have a more accurate perception of reality and more precise definitions (of intelligence, wealth, and happiness, for example)? The successes of science are proof that they do. Agreeing on good definitions is the foundation of science and the origin of the invention of computers and the modern world. But it is also the foundation of all civilization. Consensus on the definition of abstract concepts like justice is the foundation of all civilization. To build the world of tomorrow, we therefore need the best possible definitions. That is to say, we need to agree on the most accurate possible representation of the world.</p>\\n<p>I will attempt to present such a representation of the world in the remainder of this book. And, to do so, we will have to start from the beginning: the origin of the universe.</p>","toc":[{"id":"bfeef0cd-c6d6-4ca2-99ab-6b5fe27ba170","text":"","level":1,"children":[{"id":"a5128dc6-a3bb-4733-ae7e-03bbfa56a0e0","text":"Introduction","level":2,"children":[]},{"id":"fadce076-7065-4f6e-8ffd-cfb29db2b3d7","text":"Consciousness According to Modern Science","level":2,"children":[]},{"id":"08060ae3-a0dd-4e8c-a961-7aeff293635d","text":"What Is an Experience?","level":2,"children":[]},{"id":"5cdbb3a7-aed0-4b8f-b158-46618e0e43a1","text":"The Structure of Scientific Research","level":2,"children":[]},{"id":"4210e491-0a2b-44b6-acd4-e5514a954f2a","text":"Thinking Like Newton and Einstein","level":2,"children":[]},{"id":"94deef7c-68ae-4c34-beaf-269626820638","text":"The Prison of the Senses","level":2,"children":[]},{"id":"b77436e2-9505-47a5-b700-c2b0c13ff864","text":"Seeing the Invisible","level":2,"children":[]},{"id":"1a3c4e56-c16c-4ef0-802c-333f801dbcbe","text":"The Atoms of Language","level":2,"children":[]},{"id":"8155f869-3ee0-425d-9649-2edba58b54f8","text":"The Language of Thought","level":2,"children":[]},{"id":"6610f103-1342-42f8-a8d0-2811a560190c","text":"The Universality of Human Experience","level":2,"children":[]},{"id":"b3909926-9785-41de-9b44-0f0084c6ee45","text":"The Sense of Geometry","level":2,"children":[]},{"id":"9c8985b7-0ad5-402a-ba81-0c3c2cc62ddf","text":"The Sense of Numbers","level":2,"children":[]},{"id":"c7e32575-b36e-4701-959e-954a18e81684","text":"Thinking with One\'s Sex","level":2,"children":[]},{"id":"86000011-fd5a-44ed-ac0b-1e47a384ae19","text":"Psychological Bias: Bug or Feature?","level":2,"children":[]},{"id":"f9901c06-e2a5-41fb-b061-a053704021a5","text":"Understanding Dimensions","level":2,"children":[]},{"id":"353eeefd-3d64-4f82-ae67-34cb07fdbddc","text":"Multidimensional Experience","level":2,"children":[]},{"id":"9b3c3fd7-826a-4b05-a0a8-4924078e8b27","text":"Hearing Colors and Counting Space","level":2,"children":[]},{"id":"dcc438bc-6788-400a-8ceb-ec2df503244c","text":"Beyond the 3rd dimension","level":2,"children":[]},{"id":"4f7df581-daec-46f6-bb26-044096993b3b","text":"Understanding History Through War Stories","level":2,"children":[]},{"id":"dc541ca7-06fe-4176-9798-e8ad1563f21f","text":"Appearance vs. Reality, or the Prison of Symbols","level":2,"children":[]},{"id":"abc2140e-6918-41ab-992d-2289a4809d3f","text":"From Experience to Politics","level":2,"children":[]}]}],"footnotes":"<hr>\\n<section data-footnotes=\\"\\" class=\\"footnotes\\"><h2 class=\\"sr-only\\" id=\\"\\">Footnotes</h2>\\n<ol>\\n<li id=\\"user-content-fn-1\\">\\n<p>Subjective is the opposite of objective. What is objective is what exists or is true independently of the observer. What is subjective is our personal interpretation or our feelings. In other words, it is what the observer (or subject) thinks of the object. <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-1\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 1\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\"><svg class=\\"footnote-backref-icon\\" xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\" viewBox=\\"0 0 24 24\\" fill=\\"none\\" stroke=\\"currentColor\\" stroke-width=\\"2\\" stroke-linecap=\\"round\\" stroke-linejoin=\\"round\\"><path d=\\"M9 10 4 15l5 5\\"/><path d=\\"M20 4v7a4 4 0 0 1-4 4H4\\"/></svg></a></p>\\n</li>\\n<li id=\\"user-content-fn-2\\">\\n<p>As early as 1996, in the book <em>The Number Sense</em>, Stanislas Dehaene wrote: <em>\\"Functionalist cognitive psychology has almost entirely sidelined the complex question of emotions and their role in intellectual life. Yet there is no doubt that feelings should have a place in any theory of brain functions, including our current quest for the neural basis of mathematics.\\"</em> <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-2\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 2\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\"><svg class=\\"footnote-backref-icon\\" xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\" viewBox=\\"0 0 24 24\\" fill=\\"none\\" stroke=\\"currentColor\\" stroke-width=\\"2\\" stroke-linecap=\\"round\\" stroke-linejoin=\\"round\\"><path d=\\"M9 10 4 15l5 5\\"/><path d=\\"M20 4v7a4 4 0 0 1-4 4H4\\"/></svg></a></p>\\n</li>\\n<li id=\\"user-content-fn-3\\">\\n<p>In <em>The Rectangle of Lascaux</em>, Stanislas Dehaene describes experiments that shed light on the sense of numbers in certain animals. Regarding chicks, he cites the following study in particular: <a href=\\"https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19364746/\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\"><em>Elementary Arithmetic in Chicks</em></a> (Rosa Rugani, Laura Fontanari, Eleonora Simoni, Lucia Regolin, Giorgio Vallortigara) <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-3\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 3\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\"><svg class=\\"footnote-backref-icon\\" xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\" viewBox=\\"0 0 24 24\\" fill=\\"none\\" stroke=\\"currentColor\\" stroke-width=\\"2\\" stroke-linecap=\\"round\\" stroke-linejoin=\\"round\\"><path d=\\"M9 10 4 15l5 5\\"/><path d=\\"M20 4v7a4 4 0 0 1-4 4H4\\"/></svg></a> <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-3-2\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 3-2\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\">↩<sup>2</sup></a></p>\\n</li>\\n<li id=\\"user-content-fn-4\\">\\n<p>A bird that grows up alone and without a model is capable of building a nest. Similarly, a spider knows how to spin a web without prior experience. However, these \\"biological algorithms\\" for construction are not rigid. For example, birds\' experience allows them to improve and build nests more quickly or choose their building materials more effectively. In other words, while the construction program is innate, it is also adjusted by experience. See the article on this topic: <a href=\\"https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s10336-015-1214-5\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\"><em>From Neurons to Nests</em></a> (Zachary J. Hall, Simone L. Meddle &#x26; Susan D. Healy). <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-4\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 4\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\"><svg class=\\"footnote-backref-icon\\" xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\" viewBox=\\"0 0 24 24\\" fill=\\"none\\" stroke=\\"currentColor\\" stroke-width=\\"2\\" stroke-linecap=\\"round\\" stroke-linejoin=\\"round\\"><path d=\\"M9 10 4 15l5 5\\"/><path d=\\"M20 4v7a4 4 0 0 1-4 4H4\\"/></svg></a></p>\\n</li>\\n<li id=\\"user-content-fn-5\\">\\n<p>The concept of \\"subjective experience\\" that I use corresponds in a way to the term <a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Qualia\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">qualia</a>. <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-5\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 5\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\"><svg class=\\"footnote-backref-icon\\" xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\" viewBox=\\"0 0 24 24\\" fill=\\"none\\" stroke=\\"currentColor\\" stroke-width=\\"2\\" stroke-linecap=\\"round\\" stroke-linejoin=\\"round\\"><path d=\\"M9 10 4 15l5 5\\"/><path d=\\"M20 4v7a4 4 0 0 1-4 4H4\\"/></svg></a></p>\\n</li>\\n<li id=\\"user-content-fn-6\\">\\n<p>The criterion of <a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Falsifiability\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">falsifiability</a> introduced by Karl Popper to distinguish scientific theories from non-scientific ones ultimately always requires a human being to judge. That said, it is possible that AI will eventually become capable of judging what is true and what is false. This raises questions of legal liability. In fact, these questions already arise in the context of self-driving cars and air traffic control. For if an AI causes a car or plane crash while there is a human pilot on board, who is responsible? <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-6\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 6\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\"><svg class=\\"footnote-backref-icon\\" xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\" viewBox=\\"0 0 24 24\\" fill=\\"none\\" stroke=\\"currentColor\\" stroke-width=\\"2\\" stroke-linecap=\\"round\\" stroke-linejoin=\\"round\\"><path d=\\"M9 10 4 15l5 5\\"/><path d=\\"M20 4v7a4 4 0 0 1-4 4H4\\"/></svg></a></p>\\n</li>\\n<li id=\\"user-content-fn-7\\">\\n<p>We speak of \\"peer-reviewed journals\\", but this system of peer review has been in place since the 17th<sup></sup> century in a more or less formal manner. <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-7\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 7\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\"><svg class=\\"footnote-backref-icon\\" xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\" viewBox=\\"0 0 24 24\\" fill=\\"none\\" stroke=\\"currentColor\\" stroke-width=\\"2\\" stroke-linecap=\\"round\\" stroke-linejoin=\\"round\\"><path d=\\"M9 10 4 15l5 5\\"/><path d=\\"M20 4v7a4 4 0 0 1-4 4H4\\"/></svg></a></p>\\n</li>\\n<li id=\\"user-content-fn-8\\">\\n<p>G\xe9rard Noiriel, in his book <em>A Popular History of France</em>, summarizing an idea by Immanuel Kant. <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-8\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 8\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\"><svg class=\\"footnote-backref-icon\\" xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\" viewBox=\\"0 0 24 24\\" fill=\\"none\\" stroke=\\"currentColor\\" stroke-width=\\"2\\" stroke-linecap=\\"round\\" stroke-linejoin=\\"round\\"><path d=\\"M9 10 4 15l5 5\\"/><path d=\\"M20 4v7a4 4 0 0 1-4 4H4\\"/></svg></a></p>\\n</li>\\n<li id=\\"user-content-fn-9\\">\\n<p>I refer you once again to the ScienceEtonnante video: <a href=\\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lnEdBE7d_h0\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">From the Cannon to the Moon: The Discovery of Gravity</a>. <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-9\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 9\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\"><svg class=\\"footnote-backref-icon\\" xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\" viewBox=\\"0 0 24 24\\" fill=\\"none\\" stroke=\\"currentColor\\" stroke-width=\\"2\\" stroke-linecap=\\"round\\" stroke-linejoin=\\"round\\"><path d=\\"M9 10 4 15l5 5\\"/><path d=\\"M20 4v7a4 4 0 0 1-4 4H4\\"/></svg></a></p>\\n</li>\\n<li id=\\"user-content-fn-10\\">\\n<p>We could also mention the blind spot experiment conducted by high school students in science programs. See <a href=\\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JOuQa75Cu3I\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">this video</a> from the \\"Dr. Nozman\\" channel, for example. <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-10\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 10\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\"><svg class=\\"footnote-backref-icon\\" xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\" viewBox=\\"0 0 24 24\\" fill=\\"none\\" stroke=\\"currentColor\\" stroke-width=\\"2\\" stroke-linecap=\\"round\\" stroke-linejoin=\\"round\\"><path d=\\"M9 10 4 15l5 5\\"/><path d=\\"M20 4v7a4 4 0 0 1-4 4H4\\"/></svg></a></p>\\n</li>\\n<li id=\\"user-content-fn-11\\">\\n<p>If you put your head in a microwave, you won\'t feel the microwaves, but you will feel their effects. Similarly, radio waves can burn you. But your body lacks the sensors that allow your brain to interpret these waves the way your eyes do with light waves. <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-11\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 11\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\"><svg class=\\"footnote-backref-icon\\" xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\" viewBox=\\"0 0 24 24\\" fill=\\"none\\" stroke=\\"currentColor\\" stroke-width=\\"2\\" stroke-linecap=\\"round\\" stroke-linejoin=\\"round\\"><path d=\\"M9 10 4 15l5 5\\"/><path d=\\"M20 4v7a4 4 0 0 1-4 4H4\\"/></svg></a></p>\\n</li>\\n<li id=\\"user-content-fn-12\\">\\n<p>Note that almost all liquids take up less space as they cool and freeze. Water is one of the few exceptions that expands as it cools (which happens below 4 \xb0C). <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-12\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 12\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\"><svg class=\\"footnote-backref-icon\\" xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\" viewBox=\\"0 0 24 24\\" fill=\\"none\\" stroke=\\"currentColor\\" stroke-width=\\"2\\" stroke-linecap=\\"round\\" stroke-linejoin=\\"round\\"><path d=\\"M9 10 4 15l5 5\\"/><path d=\\"M20 4v7a4 4 0 0 1-4 4H4\\"/></svg></a></p>\\n</li>\\n<li id=\\"user-content-fn-13\\">\\n<p>An analogy is the act of noticing a similarity between two different things. The simplest way to make an analogy is to say, \\"X is a bit like Y\\". <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-13\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 13\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\"><svg class=\\"footnote-backref-icon\\" xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\" viewBox=\\"0 0 24 24\\" fill=\\"none\\" stroke=\\"currentColor\\" stroke-width=\\"2\\" stroke-linecap=\\"round\\" stroke-linejoin=\\"round\\"><path d=\\"M9 10 4 15l5 5\\"/><path d=\\"M20 4v7a4 4 0 0 1-4 4H4\\"/></svg></a></p>\\n</li>\\n<li id=\\"user-content-fn-14\\">\\n<p>Before the Common Era (BCE), the universal formulation of \\"Before Christ\\" (BC). <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-14\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 14\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\"><svg class=\\"footnote-backref-icon\\" xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\" viewBox=\\"0 0 24 24\\" fill=\\"none\\" stroke=\\"currentColor\\" stroke-width=\\"2\\" stroke-linecap=\\"round\\" stroke-linejoin=\\"round\\"><path d=\\"M9 10 4 15l5 5\\"/><path d=\\"M20 4v7a4 4 0 0 1-4 4H4\\"/></svg></a></p>\\n</li>\\n<li id=\\"user-content-fn-15\\">\\n<p>This is referred to as <a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anthropomorphism\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">anthropomorphism</a>. <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-15\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 15\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\"><svg class=\\"footnote-backref-icon\\" xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\" viewBox=\\"0 0 24 24\\" fill=\\"none\\" stroke=\\"currentColor\\" stroke-width=\\"2\\" stroke-linecap=\\"round\\" stroke-linejoin=\\"round\\"><path d=\\"M9 10 4 15l5 5\\"/><path d=\\"M20 4v7a4 4 0 0 1-4 4H4\\"/></svg></a></p>\\n</li>\\n<li id=\\"user-content-fn-16\\">\\n<p>Proprioception is the sense that allows us to perceive the position of our body in space and to maintain our balance, even with our eyes closed. <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-16\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 16\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\"><svg class=\\"footnote-backref-icon\\" xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\" viewBox=\\"0 0 24 24\\" fill=\\"none\\" stroke=\\"currentColor\\" stroke-width=\\"2\\" stroke-linecap=\\"round\\" stroke-linejoin=\\"round\\"><path d=\\"M9 10 4 15l5 5\\"/><path d=\\"M20 4v7a4 4 0 0 1-4 4H4\\"/></svg></a></p>\\n</li>\\n<li id=\\"user-content-fn-17\\">\\n<p>\\"Ockham\'s razor\\" is the principle that the simplest explanation is usually the correct one. <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-17\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 17\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\"><svg class=\\"footnote-backref-icon\\" xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\" viewBox=\\"0 0 24 24\\" fill=\\"none\\" stroke=\\"currentColor\\" stroke-width=\\"2\\" stroke-linecap=\\"round\\" stroke-linejoin=\\"round\\"><path d=\\"M9 10 4 15l5 5\\"/><path d=\\"M20 4v7a4 4 0 0 1-4 4H4\\"/></svg></a></p>\\n</li>\\n<li id=\\"user-content-fn-18\\">\\n<p>People with dyscalculia have difficulty with tasks as basic as figuring out what 6 minus 3 equals, or whether 6 is greater than 7. <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-18\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 18\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\"><svg class=\\"footnote-backref-icon\\" xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\" viewBox=\\"0 0 24 24\\" fill=\\"none\\" stroke=\\"currentColor\\" stroke-width=\\"2\\" stroke-linecap=\\"round\\" stroke-linejoin=\\"round\\"><path d=\\"M9 10 4 15l5 5\\"/><path d=\\"M20 4v7a4 4 0 0 1-4 4H4\\"/></svg></a></p>\\n</li>\\n<li id=\\"user-content-fn-19\\">\\n<p>On this subject, Stanislas Dehaene cites this study in particular: <em><a href=\\"https://www.pnas.org/doi/full/10.1073/pnas.2023123118\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">Sensitivity to geometric shape regularity in humans and baboons</a>: A putative signature of human singularity</em> (Mathias Sabl\xe9-Meyer, Jo\xebl Fagot, Serge Caparos, Timo van Kerkoerle, Marie Amalric, Stanislas Dehaene). <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-19\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 19\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\"><svg class=\\"footnote-backref-icon\\" xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\" viewBox=\\"0 0 24 24\\" fill=\\"none\\" stroke=\\"currentColor\\" stroke-width=\\"2\\" stroke-linecap=\\"round\\" stroke-linejoin=\\"round\\"><path d=\\"M9 10 4 15l5 5\\"/><path d=\\"M20 4v7a4 4 0 0 1-4 4H4\\"/></svg></a></p>\\n</li>\\n<li id=\\"user-content-fn-20\\">\\n<p>I have always found the term \\"discrete\\" to be unintuitive. But it shares the same etymology as \\"discern\\". It comes from the Latin <em>discernere</em>, meaning \\"to separate\\" or \\"to distinguish\\". <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-20\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 20\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\"><svg class=\\"footnote-backref-icon\\" xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\" viewBox=\\"0 0 24 24\\" fill=\\"none\\" stroke=\\"currentColor\\" stroke-width=\\"2\\" stroke-linecap=\\"round\\" stroke-linejoin=\\"round\\"><path d=\\"M9 10 4 15l5 5\\"/><path d=\\"M20 4v7a4 4 0 0 1-4 4H4\\"/></svg></a></p>\\n</li>\\n<li id=\\"user-content-fn-21\\">\\n<p>Sublimation (in psychology) refers to the process of redirecting psychic energy (such as sexual frustration) toward a constructive and socially accepted goal. For example, by engaging in a sports competition or intense work. On a larger scale, one could argue that the construction of cathedrals in medieval Europe helped channel society\'s violence. <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-21\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 21\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\"><svg class=\\"footnote-backref-icon\\" xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\" viewBox=\\"0 0 24 24\\" fill=\\"none\\" stroke=\\"currentColor\\" stroke-width=\\"2\\" stroke-linecap=\\"round\\" stroke-linejoin=\\"round\\"><path d=\\"M9 10 4 15l5 5\\"/><path d=\\"M20 4v7a4 4 0 0 1-4 4H4\\"/></svg></a></p>\\n</li>\\n<li id=\\"user-content-fn-22\\">\\n<p>Reference to the <em><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meme\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">meme</a>:</em> <em>\\"It\'s not a bug, it\'s a feature\\",</em> originating from the computer development community. Originally, it was a joke, but we can expand on it by asking whether what appears to be a problem is actually a problem or, on the contrary, is beneficial—and to whom. <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-22\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 22\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\"><svg class=\\"footnote-backref-icon\\" xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\" viewBox=\\"0 0 24 24\\" fill=\\"none\\" stroke=\\"currentColor\\" stroke-width=\\"2\\" stroke-linecap=\\"round\\" stroke-linejoin=\\"round\\"><path d=\\"M9 10 4 15l5 5\\"/><path d=\\"M20 4v7a4 4 0 0 1-4 4H4\\"/></svg></a></p>\\n</li>\\n<li id=\\"user-content-fn-23\\">\\n<p>On human psychology in combat, see, for example, <em>Sous le feu – La mort comme hypoth\xe8se de travail</em> by Michel Goya (not available in English). <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-23\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 23\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\"><svg class=\\"footnote-backref-icon\\" xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\" viewBox=\\"0 0 24 24\\" fill=\\"none\\" stroke=\\"currentColor\\" stroke-width=\\"2\\" stroke-linecap=\\"round\\" stroke-linejoin=\\"round\\"><path d=\\"M9 10 4 15l5 5\\"/><path d=\\"M20 4v7a4 4 0 0 1-4 4H4\\"/></svg></a></p>\\n</li>\\n<li id=\\"user-content-fn-24\\">\\n<p>Another example of \\"projection\\" is empathy. We never truly access what others are experiencing. Empathy is always a projection of our own experiences onto others. And it is an extremely powerful tool for understanding the world. Because it allows us to project our minds to see the world through the eyes of others. Basically, it comes down to asking: <em>\\"If I were in this person\'s shoes, what would my experience, my feelings, and my thoughts be?\\"</em> <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-24\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 24\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\"><svg class=\\"footnote-backref-icon\\" xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\" viewBox=\\"0 0 24 24\\" fill=\\"none\\" stroke=\\"currentColor\\" stroke-width=\\"2\\" stroke-linecap=\\"round\\" stroke-linejoin=\\"round\\"><path d=\\"M9 10 4 15l5 5\\"/><path d=\\"M20 4v7a4 4 0 0 1-4 4H4\\"/></svg></a> <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-24-2\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 24-2\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\">↩<sup>2</sup></a></p>\\n</li>\\n<li id=\\"user-content-fn-25\\">\\n<p>The \\"friend zone\\" refers to a situation in which one person has romantic or sexual feelings for someone who only wants to maintain a friendship with them. Generally, this situation is definitive. <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-25\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 25\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\"><svg class=\\"footnote-backref-icon\\" xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\" viewBox=\\"0 0 24 24\\" fill=\\"none\\" stroke=\\"currentColor\\" stroke-width=\\"2\\" stroke-linecap=\\"round\\" stroke-linejoin=\\"round\\"><path d=\\"M9 10 4 15l5 5\\"/><path d=\\"M20 4v7a4 4 0 0 1-4 4H4\\"/></svg></a></p>\\n</li>\\n<li id=\\"user-content-fn-26\\">\\n<p>In this regard, the idea of \\"thinking outside the box\\" can be interpreted as: perceiving a dimension that others have not seen. Knowing that a problem that has no solution in 2D may have one in 3D. Similarly, \\"stepping out of <a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Allegory_of_the_cave\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">Plato\'s cave</a>\\" corresponds to the discovery of new dimensions that enrich one\'s perception of reality. <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-26\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 26\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\"><svg class=\\"footnote-backref-icon\\" xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\" viewBox=\\"0 0 24 24\\" fill=\\"none\\" stroke=\\"currentColor\\" stroke-width=\\"2\\" stroke-linecap=\\"round\\" stroke-linejoin=\\"round\\"><path d=\\"M9 10 4 15l5 5\\"/><path d=\\"M20 4v7a4 4 0 0 1-4 4H4\\"/></svg></a></p>\\n</li>\\n<li id=\\"user-content-fn-27\\">\\n<p>We can consider the \\"social status\\" we assign to those around us to be a kind of weighted average of all the dimensions we perceive about them. <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-27\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 27\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\"><svg class=\\"footnote-backref-icon\\" xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\" viewBox=\\"0 0 24 24\\" fill=\\"none\\" stroke=\\"currentColor\\" stroke-width=\\"2\\" stroke-linecap=\\"round\\" stroke-linejoin=\\"round\\"><path d=\\"M9 10 4 15l5 5\\"/><path d=\\"M20 4v7a4 4 0 0 1-4 4H4\\"/></svg></a></p>\\n</li>\\n<li id=\\"user-content-fn-28\\">\\n<p>Numerous scientific studies highlight this influence. For example, <a href=\\"https://link.springer.com/article/10.1186/s13411-015-0031-3\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\"><em>On the psychological impact of food color</em></a> (Charles Spence) or <a href=\\"https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S1878450X23000112\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\"><em>The influence of music on the perception of taste</em></a> (Joana Campinho, Paulo Sousa, Paulina Mata). <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-28\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 28\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\"><svg class=\\"footnote-backref-icon\\" xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\" viewBox=\\"0 0 24 24\\" fill=\\"none\\" stroke=\\"currentColor\\" stroke-width=\\"2\\" stroke-linecap=\\"round\\" stroke-linejoin=\\"round\\"><path d=\\"M9 10 4 15l5 5\\"/><path d=\\"M20 4v7a4 4 0 0 1-4 4H4\\"/></svg></a></p>\\n</li>\\n<li id=\\"user-content-fn-29\\">\\n<p>Today, in terms of raw computing power, AIs are <em>in principle</em> on par with the human brain. The difference in performance lies in their structure. The human brain comprises a multitude of specialized processors that have been pre-trained on reality through 3.8 billion years of evolution. And, above all, all these processors communicate with one another in a highly efficient manner compared to current AIs. ChatGPT is already a cross-modal (or multimodal) AI capable of handling text and images, but this pales in comparison to the multimodality of the human brain. And this obstacle likely has no chance of being resolved simply by increasing computational power. <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-29\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 29\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\"><svg class=\\"footnote-backref-icon\\" xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\" viewBox=\\"0 0 24 24\\" fill=\\"none\\" stroke=\\"currentColor\\" stroke-width=\\"2\\" stroke-linecap=\\"round\\" stroke-linejoin=\\"round\\"><path d=\\"M9 10 4 15l5 5\\"/><path d=\\"M20 4v7a4 4 0 0 1-4 4H4\\"/></svg></a></p>\\n</li>\\n<li id=\\"user-content-fn-30\\">\\n<p>Regarding the existence of a number line in chicks, Stanislas Dehaene cites this article in particular: <a href=\\"https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25635096/\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\"><em>Animal Cognition</em></a>: the spatial representation of numbers in newborn chicks resembles the human mental number line (Rosa Rugani, Giorgio Vallortigara, Konstantinos Priftis, Lucia Regolin). <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-30\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 30\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\"><svg class=\\"footnote-backref-icon\\" xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\" viewBox=\\"0 0 24 24\\" fill=\\"none\\" stroke=\\"currentColor\\" stroke-width=\\"2\\" stroke-linecap=\\"round\\" stroke-linejoin=\\"round\\"><path d=\\"M9 10 4 15l5 5\\"/><path d=\\"M20 4v7a4 4 0 0 1-4 4H4\\"/></svg></a></p>\\n</li>\\n<li id=\\"user-content-fn-31\\">\\n<p>Quote from the book in question: <em>\\"It is only with the heart that one can see rightly. What is essential is invisible to the eye.\\"</em> <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-31\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 31\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\"><svg class=\\"footnote-backref-icon\\" xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\" viewBox=\\"0 0 24 24\\" fill=\\"none\\" stroke=\\"currentColor\\" stroke-width=\\"2\\" stroke-linecap=\\"round\\" stroke-linejoin=\\"round\\"><path d=\\"M9 10 4 15l5 5\\"/><path d=\\"M20 4v7a4 4 0 0 1-4 4H4\\"/></svg></a></p>\\n</li>\\n<li id=\\"user-content-fn-32\\">\\n<p>For example, prime numbers are those that cannot be arranged in a rectangle. Concretely, there is no rectangular egg carton that can be completely filled with 3, 5, 7, 11, 13, or 17 eggs, etc. Given that a prime number is a number that can only be divided by 1 and itself. <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-32\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 32\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\"><svg class=\\"footnote-backref-icon\\" xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\" viewBox=\\"0 0 24 24\\" fill=\\"none\\" stroke=\\"currentColor\\" stroke-width=\\"2\\" stroke-linecap=\\"round\\" stroke-linejoin=\\"round\\"><path d=\\"M9 10 4 15l5 5\\"/><path d=\\"M20 4v7a4 4 0 0 1-4 4H4\\"/></svg></a></p>\\n</li>\\n<li id=\\"user-content-fn-33\\">\\n<p>It is not that we understand only what we already know, but that we understand only what we can connect to what we already know. <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-33\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 33\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\"><svg class=\\"footnote-backref-icon\\" xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\" viewBox=\\"0 0 24 24\\" fill=\\"none\\" stroke=\\"currentColor\\" stroke-width=\\"2\\" stroke-linecap=\\"round\\" stroke-linejoin=\\"round\\"><path d=\\"M9 10 4 15l5 5\\"/><path d=\\"M20 4v7a4 4 0 0 1-4 4H4\\"/></svg></a></p>\\n</li>\\n<li id=\\"user-content-fn-34\\">\\n<p>It would not be surprising if national identities emerged on the day the majority of the population gained access to a world map. For one to feel a sense of belonging to a territory, one must first be able to clearly visualize that territory. And that is far from obvious without a map or means of transportation. <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-34\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 34\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\"><svg class=\\"footnote-backref-icon\\" xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\" viewBox=\\"0 0 24 24\\" fill=\\"none\\" stroke=\\"currentColor\\" stroke-width=\\"2\\" stroke-linecap=\\"round\\" stroke-linejoin=\\"round\\"><path d=\\"M9 10 4 15l5 5\\"/><path d=\\"M20 4v7a4 4 0 0 1-4 4H4\\"/></svg></a></p>\\n</li>\\n<li id=\\"user-content-fn-35\\">\\n<p>The invention of stories to convey ideas and information was likely the first great intellectual revolution in human history. <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-35\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 35\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\"><svg class=\\"footnote-backref-icon\\" xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\" viewBox=\\"0 0 24 24\\" fill=\\"none\\" stroke=\\"currentColor\\" stroke-width=\\"2\\" stroke-linecap=\\"round\\" stroke-linejoin=\\"round\\"><path d=\\"M9 10 4 15l5 5\\"/><path d=\\"M20 4v7a4 4 0 0 1-4 4H4\\"/></svg></a></p>\\n</li>\\n<li id=\\"user-content-fn-36\\">\\n<p>That is why I try to use the simplest possible language and find concrete examples to illustrate my ideas. I realize that this may make my text unappealing to some, but what this book loses in prestige, it gains in accessibility. More broadly, if I didn\'t make an effort to make my ideas accessible, only those fortunate enough to have the prior experience to understand would grasp them. Concretely, if I had told you about a 50-dimensional space without first explaining what a dimension is, only those already familiar with dimensions would have been able to understand what I was talking about. <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-36\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 36\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\"><svg class=\\"footnote-backref-icon\\" xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\" viewBox=\\"0 0 24 24\\" fill=\\"none\\" stroke=\\"currentColor\\" stroke-width=\\"2\\" stroke-linecap=\\"round\\" stroke-linejoin=\\"round\\"><path d=\\"M9 10 4 15l5 5\\"/><path d=\\"M20 4v7a4 4 0 0 1-4 4H4\\"/></svg></a></p>\\n</li>\\n<li id=\\"user-content-fn-37\\">\\n<p>When the mathematician Ramanujan said he received certain mathematical formulas in his dreams from the goddess Namagiri, he was likely describing in a romanticized way this \\"verbalization of an intuition resulting from unconscious work\\". <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-37\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 37\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\"><svg class=\\"footnote-backref-icon\\" xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\" viewBox=\\"0 0 24 24\\" fill=\\"none\\" stroke=\\"currentColor\\" stroke-width=\\"2\\" stroke-linecap=\\"round\\" stroke-linejoin=\\"round\\"><path d=\\"M9 10 4 15l5 5\\"/><path d=\\"M20 4v7a4 4 0 0 1-4 4H4\\"/></svg></a></p>\\n</li>\\n</ol>\\n</section>","frontmatter":{}}}')}}]);